\par }{\fs22 Geoffrey Shafer, dashingly outfitted in a single-breasted blue blazer, white shirt, striped tie and narrow gray trousers from H. Huntsman & Son, walked out of his town house at seven thirty in the morning and climbed into a black Jaguar XJ12.}{
\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He backed the Jag slowly out of the driveway, then stepped on the accelerator.  The sleek sports car rocketed up to fifty before it reached the stop sign at Connecticut Avenue, in the posh Kalorama section of Washington, DC.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 When Shafer reached the busy intersection, he didn\rquote t stop.  He floored the accelerator, picking up more speed.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He was doing sixty-five and ached to crash the Jag into the stately fieldstone wall bordering the avenue.  He aimed the Jag closer to the wall.  He could see the head-on collision, visualize it, feel it all over.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 At the last possible second, he tried to avoid the deadly crash.  He spun the wheel hard to the left.  The sports car fishtailed all the way across the avenue, tires screeching and burning, the smell of rubber thick in the air.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 The Jag skidded to a stop, headed the wrong way on the street, the windshield issuing its glossy black stare at a barrage of early oncoming traffic.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 Shafer stepped on the accelerator again, and headed forward against}{\i\fs22  }{\fs22 the oncoming traffic.  Every car and truck began to honk loud, sustained blasts.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 Shafer didn\rquote t even try to catch his breath or bearings.  He sped along the avenue, gaining speed.  He zoomed across Rock Creek Bridge, made a left, then another left into Rock Creek Parkway.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 A tiny scream of pain escaped from his lips.  It was involuntary, coming swiftly and unexpectedly.  A moment of fear, weakness.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He floored the pedal again and the engine roared.  He was doing seventy, then pressing to eighty.  He zigged and zagged around slower-moving sedans, sport-utility vehicles, a soot-covered A&P delivery truck.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 Only a few honked now.  Other drivers on the parkway were terrified, scared out of their minds.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He exited the Rock Creek Parkway at fifty miles an hour, then he gunned it again.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 P Street was even more crowded at that hour than the parkway had been.  Washington was just waking up and setting off to work.  He could still see}{\i\fs22  }{\fs22 that inviting stone wall on Connecticut.  He shouldn\rquote t have sto
pped.  He began searching for another rock-solid object, looking for something to hit very hard.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He was doing eighty miles an hour as he approached Dupont Circle.  He shot forward like a ground rocket.  Two lines of traffic were backed up at a red light.  No way out of this one, he thought.  Nowhere to go left or right.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He didn\rquote t want to rear-end a dozen cars!  That was no way to end this - end his life - by smashing into a commonplace Chevy Caprice, a Honda Accord, a delivery truck.  }{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He swerved violently 
to the left and veered into the lanes of traffic coming east, coming right at him.  He could see the panicked, disbelieving faces behind the dusty, grime-smeared windshields.  The horns started to blast, a high-pitched symphony of fear.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He ran the next light and just barely squeezed between an oncoming Jeep and a concrete-mixer truck.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 He sped down M Street, then onto Pennsylvania Avenue, and headed toward Washington Circle.  The George Washington University Medical Center was up ahead - a perfect ending?}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 The Metro patrolcar appeared out of nowhere, its siren-bullhorn screaming in protest, its rotating beacon glittering, signaling for him to pull over.  Shafer slowed down and pulled to the curb.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 The cop hurried to Shafer\rquote s car, his hand on his holster.  He looked frightened and unsure.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 \lquote Get out of the car, sir}{\fs22\lang2057 ,\rquote }{\fs22  the cop said in a commanding voice.  \lquote Get out of the car right now.\rquote }{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 Shafer suddenly felt calm and relaxed.  There was no tension left in his body.}{\fs24 
\par \sect }\sectd \linex0\sectdefaultcl \pard\plain \nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20 {\fs22 \lquote All right.  All right.  I\rquote m getting out.  No problem.\rquote }{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 \lquote You know how fast you were going?\rquote  the cop asked in an agitated voice, his face flushed a bright red.  Shafer noticed that his hand was still on his gun.}{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 Shafer pursed his lips, thought about his answer.  \lquote Well - I\rquote d say about thirty, Officer,\rquote  he finally said.  \lquote Maybe a little over the speed limit.\rquote }{\fs24 
\par }{\fs22 Then he took out an ID card and handed it over.  \lquote But you can\rquote t do anything about it.  I\rquote m with the British Embassy.  I have diplomatic immunity.\rquote 
