\par Things were going pretty well that day
.  I was driving a bright-orange school bus through Southeast on a blistering-hot morning in late July and I was whistling a little Al Green as I drove.  I was in the process of picking up sixteen boys from their houses and also two foster homes.  Door-to
-door bus service.  Hard to beat.
\par Just one week earlier I had returned from Boston and the Mr. Smith murder case.  Mr. Smith and a deranged killer named Gary Soneji had both been involved in that one.  I needed a rest and I\rquote d taken the morning off to do something I\rquote 
d been looking forward to for a change.
\par My partner, John Sampson, and a twelve-year-old named Enrol Mignault sat behind me on the bus.  John was wearing Wayfarer shades, black jeans, a black T-shirt that read: ALLIANCE OF CONCERNED MEN.  SEND DONA
TIONS TODAY.  He is six-nine, a very solid two hundred fifty pounds.  We\rquote ve been friends since we were ten, when I first moved to DC.
\par He, Errol, and I were talking about the boxer Sugar Ray Robinson, almost shouting over the bus\rquote s blustery, occasionally misfiring engine.  Sampson had his huge arm lightly draped over Errol\rquote 
s shoulders.  Proper physical contact is encouraged when dealing with these boys.
\par Finally, we picked up the last little guy on our list, an eight-year-old who lived in Benning Terrace, a tough project known to some of us as Simple City.
\par As we left the project, an ugly smear of graffiti told visitors everything they needed to know about the neighborhood.  It read: YOU ARE NOW LEAVING THE WAR ZONE, AND YOU LIVED TO TELL ABOUT IT.
\par We were taki
ng the boys out to Lorton Prison in Virginia.  They would be visiting their fathers for the afternoon.  They were all young, between eight and thirteen.  The Alliance transports forty to fifty kids each week to see their fathers and mothers in different p
risons.  The goal is a lofty one: to bring the crime rate in Washington down by a third.
\par I\rquote d been out to the prison more times than I cared to remember.  I knew the warden at Lorton pretty well.  A few years back I\rquote d spent a lifetime there, interviewing Gary Soneji.
\par Warden Marion Campbell had set up a large room on level one, where the boys met with their fathers.  It was a powerful scene, even more emotional than I\rquote d expected.  The Alliance spends time training the fathers who want to participate in the pro
gram.  There are four steps: how to show love; accept fault and responsibility; attain parent and child harmonies; new beginnings.
\par Ironically the boys were all trying to look and act tougher than they actually were.  I heard one boy say, You weren\rquote t in my life before, why should I listen to you now?\rquote  But the fathers were trying to show a softer side.
\par Sampson and I hadn\rquote t made the run to Lorton before.  It was our first time, but I was already sure I\rquote d do it again.  There was so much raw emotion and hope in 
the room, so much potential for something good and decent.  Even if some of it would never be realized, it showed that an effort was being made, and something positive could come from it.
\par What struck me most was the bond that still existed between some of 
the fathers and their young sons.  I thought about my own boy, Damon, and how lucky we were.  The thing about most of the prisoners in Lorton was that they knew what they had done was wrong; they just didn\rquote t know how to stop doing it.
\par For most of the hour and a half, I just walked around and listened.  I was occasionally needed as a psychologist, and I did the best I could on short notice.  At one little group, I heard a father say, \lquote 
Please tell your mother I love her and I miss her like crazy.\rquote   Then both the prisoner and his son broke into tears and hugged one another fiercely.
\par Sampson came up to me after we\rquote d been in the prison for an hour or so.  He was grinning broadly.  His smile, when it comes, is a killer.  \lquote Man, I love this.  Do-gooder shit is the best.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah, I\rquote m hooked myself.  I\rquote ll drive the big orange bus again.\rquote 
\par \lquote Think it\rquote ll help?  Fathers and sons meeting like this?\rquote  he asked me.
\par I looked around the room.  \lquote I think today, right now, this is a success for these men and their sons.  That\rquote s good enough.\rquote 
\par Sampson nodded.  \lquote The old one-day-at-a-time approach.  Works for me, too.  I am flying, Alex.\rquote 
\par So was I, so was I.  I\rquote m a sucker for this kind of stuff.
\par As I drove the young boys home that afternoon, I could see by their faces that they\rquote d had positive experiences with their fathers.  The boys weren\rquote t nearly as noisy and rambunctious on the way back to DC.  They weren\rquote 
t trying to be so tough.  They were just acting like kids.
\par Almost every one of the boys thanked Sampson and me as they got off the big orange bus.  It wasn\rquote t necessary.  It sure was a lot better than chasing after homicidal maniacs.
\par The last boy we dropped off was the eight-year-old from Benning Terrace.  He hugged both John and me and then he started to cry.  \lquote I miss my dad,\rquote  he said, before running home.
