\par That night, Sampson and I were on duty in Southeast.  We\rquote re senior homicide detectives and I\rquote m also liaison between the FBI and the DC police.  We got a call at about half past midnight telling us to go to the area of Wa
shington called Shaw.  There\rquote d been a bad homicide.
\par A lone Metro squad car was at the murder scene, and the neighborhood psychos had turned out in pretty fair numbers.
\par It looked like a bizarre block party in the middle of hell.  Fires were blazing nearby, throwing off sparks in two trash barrels, which made no sense, given the sweltering heat of the night.
\par The victim was a young woman, probably between fourteen and her late teens, according to the radio report.
\par She wasn\rquote t hard to find.  Her nude, mutilated body had been discarded in a clump of briar bushes in a small park, less than ten yards off a paved pathway.
\par As Sampson and I approached the body, a boy shouted at us from the other side of the crime tape.  \lquote To, yo, she\rquote s just some street whore!\rquote 
\par I stopped and looked at him.  He reminded me of the boys we\rquote d just transported to Lorton Prison.  \lquote Dime-a-dozen bitch.  Not worth your time, or mine, dee-fectives,\rquote  he went on with his disturbing rap.
\par I finally walked up to the young wisecracker.  \lquote How do you know that?  You seen her around?\rquote 
\par The boy backed off.  But then he grinned, showing off a gold star on one of his front teeth.  \lquote She ain\rquote t got no clothes on an\rquote  she layin\rquote  on her back.  Somebody stick her good.  Sure sound like a whore to me.\rquote 
\par Sampson eyed the youth, who looked to be around fourteen, but might have been even younger.  \lquote You know who she is?\rquote 
\par \lquote Hell, no\rquote  The boy pretended to be insulted.  \lquote Don\rquote t know no whores, man.\rquote 
\par The boy finally swaggered off, looking back at us once or twice, shaking his head.  Sampson and I walked on and joined two uniformed cops standing by the body.  They were obviously waiting for reinforcements.  Apparently, we were it.
\par \lquote You call Emergency Services?\rquote   I asked the uniforms.
\par \lquote Thirty-five minutes ago, and counting,\rquote  said the older-looking of the two.  He was probably in his late twenties, sporting an attempted mustache and trying to look like he was experienced at scenes like this one.
\par \lquote That figures.\rquote  I shook my head.  You find any ID anywhere around here?\rquote 
\par \lquote No ID.  We looked around in the bushes.  Nothing but the body,\rquote  said the younger one.  \lquote And the body\rquote s seen better days.\rquote   He was perspiring badly and looked a little sick.
\par I put on latex gloves and bent down over the corpse.  She did appear to be in her mid to late teens.  The girl\rquote s throat had been slit from ear to ear.  Her face was badly slashed.  So were the soles of her feet, which seemed odd.  She\rquote 
d been stabbed a dozen or more times in her chest and stomach.  I pushed open her legs.
\par I saw something, and it made me sick.  A metal handle was barely visible between her legs.  I was almost sure it was a knife and that it had been driven all the way into her vagina.
\par Sampson crouched and looked at me.  \lquote What are you thinking, Alex?  Another one?\rquote 
