\par I was at the homicide scene for a little over two hours, much longer than I wanted to be there, and I hated every second.  I couldn\rquote t fix a set pattern for the Jane Doe killings, and Nina Quids\rquote  murder didn\rquote 
t help.  Why had he struck her so many times and so savagely?   What were the flowers doing there?   Could this be the work of the same killer?
\par The way I usually operate at a crime scene, the homicide investigation takes on an almost aerial view.  Everything emanates from the body.
\par Sampson and I walked the entire crime scene - from the basement to each floor and on up to the roof.  Then we walked the neighborhood.  Nobody had seen anything unusual, which didn\rquote t surprise either of us.
\par Now came the really bad part.  Sampson and I drove from the woeful tenement to Nina\rquote s apartment in the Brookland section of Washington, east of Catholic University.  I knew I was being sucked in again, but there was nothing I could do about it.

\par It was a sweltering-hot day and the sun hammered Washington without mercy.  We were both silent and withdrawn during the ride.  What we had to do was the worst thing about our job, telling a family about the death of a loved one.  I didn\rquote 
t know how I could do it this time.
\par Nina lived in a well-kept brown-brick building on Monroe Street.  Miniature yellow roses were blooming out front in bright-green window-boxes.  It didn\rquote 
t look as if anything bad should happen to someone who lived here.  Everything about the place was so bright and hopeful, just as Nina had been.
\par I was becoming more and more disturbed and upset about the brutal and obscene murder, and the fact that it probably wouldn\rquote 
t get a decent investigation from the department, at least not officially.  Nana Mama would chalk it up to her conspiracy theories about the white overlords and their \lquote criminal disinterest\rquote 
 in the people of Southeast.  She had often told me that she felt morally superior to white people, that she would never, ever treat them the way they treated the black people of Washington.
\par \lquote Nina\rquote s sister, Marie, takes care of the kids\rquote  Sampson said as we rode down Monroe.  \lquote She\rquote 
s a nice girl.  Had a drug problem one time, beat it.  Nina helped her.  The whole family is close-knit.  A lot like yours.  This is going to be real bad, Alex.\rquote 
\par I turned to him.  Not surprisingly, he was taking Nina\rquote s death even harder than I was.  It\rquote s unusual for him to show his emotions though.  \lquote I can do it, John.  You stay here in the car.  I\rquote ll go up and talk to the family.
\rquote 
\par Sampson shook his head and sighed loudly.  \lquote Doesn\rquote t work that way, sugar.\rquote 
\par He snugged the Nissan up to the curb and we both climbed out.  He didn\rquote t stop me from coming along to the apartment, so I knew he wanted me there with him.  He was right.  This was going to be bad.
\par The Child\rquote s apartment took up the first and second floors.  The front door was slightly ornate, aluminum.  Nina\rquote 
s husband was already at the door.  He had on the proletariat uniform of the DC Housing Authority where he worked: mud-stained work boots, blue trousers, a shirt marked DCHA.  One of the babies snuggled in his
 arms, a beautiful girl who looked at me and smiled and cooed.
\par \lquote Could we come inside for a moment?\rquote   Sampson asked.
\par \lquote It\rquote s Nina\rquote  the husband said, and started to break down right there in the doorway.
\par \lquote I\rquote m sorry, William.\rquote   I spoke softly.  \lquote You\rquote re right.  She\rquote s dead.  She\rquote s been killed.  She was found this morning.\rquote 
\par William Childs started to sob loudly.  He was a powerful-looking working man, but that didn\rquote t matter.  He held his bewildered little girl to his chest and tried to control the crying, but he couldn\rquote t.
\par \lquote Oh God, no.  Oh, Nina, Nina baby.  How could somebody kill her?  How could anybody do that?   Oh, Nina, Nina, Nina.\rquote 
\par A young, pretty woman came up behind him.  She had to be Nina\rquote s sister, Marie.  She took the baby from her sister\rquote s husband, and th
e little girl began to scream, as if she knew what had happened.  I had seen so many families, so many good people, who had lost loved ones on these merciless streets.  I knew it would never completely stop, but I felt it ought to get better, and it never
 did.
\par The sister motioned for us to come inside, and I noticed a hall table on which were two pocketbooks, as if Nina were still about.  The apartment was comfortable and neat, with light bamboo and white-cushioned furniture.  The whirr of a window air-cond
itioner was constant.  A Lladro porcelain figure of a nurse was on an end table.
\par I was still sorting through details about the homicide scene, trying to connect the murder to the other Jane Does.  We learned that Nina had attended a health-care charity din
ner on Saturday night.  William had been working overtime.  The family called the police late Saturday night.  Two detectives had shown up, but no one had been able to find Nina until now.
\par Then I was holding the baby, while Nina\rquote s sister took the chill off
 a bottle of formula.  It was such a sad and poignant moment, knowing this poor little girl would never see her mother again, never know how truly special her mother had been.  It reminded me of my own kids and their mother, and of Christine, who was afra
id I would die during some murder investigation like this one.
\par The older little girl came up to me while I was holding her baby sister.  She was two or three at the most.  \lquote I got a new hairstyle,\rquote  she said proudly and did a half-turn to show me.
\par \lquote You did?   It\rquote s beautiful.  Who did those braids for you?\rquote 
\par \lquote My mommy\rquote  said the girl.
\par It was an hour later that Sampson and I finally left the house.  We drove away in silence and despair, the same way we\rquote d come.  After a couple of blocks, Sampson pulled over in fron
t of a ramshackle neighborhood bodega covered with beer and soda posters.
\par He gave a deep sigh, put his hands to his face, and then John cried.  I\rquote d never, ever seen him like this before, not in all the years we\rquote d been friends, not even when we were just bo
ys.  I reached out and laid a hand on his shoulder, and he didn\rquote t move away.  Then he told me something he hadn\rquote t shared before.
\par \lquote I loved her, Alex, but I let her get away.  I never told her how I felt.  We have to get this sonofabitch.\rquote 
\par 
