\par I sensed I was at the start of another homicide mess.  I didn\rquote t want it, but I couldn\rquote t stop the horror.  I had to try to do something about the Jane Does.  I couldn\rquote t just stand by and do nothing.
\par Although I was assigned to the Seventh District as a senior detective, my job as liaison with the FBI gave me some extra status and also freedom to occasionally work without too much supervision or interference.  My mind was running free and I\rquote 
d already made some associations with Nina\rquote s murder and at least some 
of the unsolved killings.  First, there had been no identification on the victims at the crime scenes.  Second, the bodies had frequently been dumped in buildings where they might not be found quickly.  Third, not a single witness had seen anyone who migh
t be a suspect or the killer.  The most we ever got was that there had been traffic, or people out on the streets, where one of the bodies had been found.  That told me that the killer knew how to blend in, and that he possibly was a black man.
\par Around six that night, I finally headed home.  This was supposed to be a day off.  I had things to do there, and I was trying to balance the demands of the job and home life as best I could.  I put on a happy face and headed inside the house.
\par Damon, Jannie, and Nana were singing \lquote Sit Down You\rquote re Rockin\rquote de Boat\rquote 
 in the kitchen.  The show tune was music to my ears and other essential parts of my anatomy.  The kids looked happy as could be.  There is a lot to be said for the innocence of childhood.
\par I heard Nana say, \lquote How about "I Can Tell The World"?\rquote   Then the three of them launched into one of the most beautiful spirituals I know.  Damon\rquote s voice seemed particularly strong to me.  I hadn\rquote t really noticed that before.

\par \lquote I feel like I just walked into a story by Louisa May Alcott,\rquote  I said, laughing for the first time that long day.
\par \lquote I take that as a high compliment,\rquote  Nana said.  She was somewhere between her late seventies and early eighties now, but not telling, and also not showing her age.
\par \lquote Who\rquote s Louise Maise Alcott?\rquote  Jannie said, and made a lemon-sucking face.  She is a healthy little skeptic, though almost never a cynic.  In that way, she takes after both her father and grandmother.
\par \lquote Look it up tonight, little one.  Fifty cents in your pocket for the correct answer,\rquote  I told her.
\par \lquote You\rquote re on.\rquote Jannie grinned.  \lquote You can pay me right now if you like.\rquote 
\par \lquote Me too?\rquote   Damon asked.
\par \lquote Of course.  You can look up Jane Austen,\rquote  I said to him.  \lquote Now what\rquote s with the heavenly harmonizing?   I like it very much, by the way.  I just want to know what the special occasion is.\rquote 
\par \lquote We\rquote re just singing while we prepare dinner,\rquote  Nana said, and stuck up her nose and twinkled her eyes.  \lquote You play jazz and the blues on the piano, don\rquote 
t you?   We harmonize like angels sometimes.  No special reason necessary.  Good for the soul, and the soul food, I suppose.  Can\rquote t hurt.\rquote 
\par \lquote Well, don\rquote t stop singing on my account,\rquote  I said, but they had already stopped.  Too bad.  Something was going on.  I\rquote d figured out that much.  A musical mystery to be solved in my own house.
\par \lquote We still on for boxing after dinner?\rquote   I asked cautiously.  I was feeling a little vulnerable because I didn\rquote t want them to turn me down for the boxing lesson that has become a ritual.
\par \lquote Of course,\rquote  Damon said, and frowned like I must be out of my mind to even ask such a question.
\par \lquote Of course.  Pshaw.  Why wouldn\rquote t we be?\rquote   Jannie said, and brushed off my silly question with a wave of her hand.  \lquote How\rquote s Ms Johnson?\rquote   she asked then.  \lquote You two talk today?\rquote 
\par \lquote I still want to know what the singing was all about?\rquote   I answered Jannie with a question of my own.
\par \lquote You have valuable information.  Well, so do I.  Tit for tat,\rquote  she said.  \ldblquote How do you like that?\rquote 
\par A little later, I decided to call Christine at home.  Lately, it had seemed more like the way it had been between us before I got involved with the Mr. Smith case.  We talked for a while, and then I asked her to go out on Friday.
\par \lquote Of course.  I\rquote d like that, Alex.  What should I wear?\rquote   she asked.
\par I hesitated.  \lquote Well, I always like what you choose - but wear something special.\rquote 
\par She didn\rquote t ask why.
