\par Something was up, and I didn\rquote t think that I\rquote d like it very much.  I arrived at the Seventh District Police Station just before seven thirty that morning.  I\rquote 
d been summoned by the powers-that-be to the station, and it was a tough deal.  I\rquote d worked until two in the morning trying to get a lead on Nina Childs\rquote  murder.
\par I had a feeling that the day was starting out wrong.  I was tense and more uptight than I usually let myself become.  I didn\rquote t like this early-morning command appearance one bit.
\par I shook my head, frowned, t
ried to roll the kinks out of my neck.  Finally, I gritted my teeth tightly before opening the mahogany-wood door.  Chief of Detectives George Pittman was lying in wait in his office, which consisted of three connecting offices, including a conference roo
m.
\par The Jefe, as he\rquote s called by his many \lquote admirers\rquote 
, had on a boxy gray business suit, overstarched white shirt, a silver necktie.  His gray-and-white-streaked hair was slicked back.  He looked like a banker, and in some ways he was.  As he never tires of sa
ying, he is working with a fixed budget, and is always mindful of manpower costs, overtime costs, caseload costs.  Apparently, he is an efficient manager, which is why the police commissioner overlooks the fact that he\rquote 
s a bully, bigot, racist and careerist.
\par Up on his wall were three large, important-looking pushpin maps.  The first showed two consecutive months of rapes, homicides, and assaults in Washington.  The second map did the same for residential and commercial burglaries.  The third map showed auto
