\par Early the next morning I was back in the write-up room at the Seventh District Station working on the John Doe homicide.  I was the first one in there.
\par Apparently, no one had noticed Frank Odenkirk as he was leaving the airport.  His clothing still hadn\rquote t been recovered.  The ME reported that he had definitely been sodomized after he\rquote 
d been killed.  As I had suspected, there was no semen.  The killer had used a condom.  Just as with the Jane Does.
\par The police commissioner was involved in the O
denkirk case, and was putting added pressure on the department.  It was making everyone angry and a little crazy.  Chief Pittman was riding his detectives hard, and the only case he seemed interested in was the Odenkirk killing, especially since a suspect
 in the German tourist murder had been arrested.
\par At around eleven that morning, Rakeem Powell stopped by my desk.  He bent low and whispered, \lquote Might have something interesting, Alex.  Downstairs in the jail, if you\rquote ve got a minute.  Could be a first break o
n those two murdered girls in Shaw.\rquote 
\par The jail was down a set of steep concrete stairs, just past a tight warren of small interrogation rooms, a holding room and a booking room.  All over the ceiling and walls, prisoners had scratched their street names or 
used black ink from fingerprinting to write the names.  This was incredibly dumb of them, since it gave us their street names for our files.
\par It\rquote s purposely kept dark down in the jail.  Each cell is six by five feet, with a metal bed and a combination water fountain/toilet.  Sneakers had been tossed in the hallways outside several of the cells.  It\rquote 
s what experienced prisoners do who don\rquote t want to take the laces out of their sneakers.  Laces aren\rquote t allowed in the jail for safety reasons.
\par A small-time drug runner and petty thief named Alfred \lquote Sneak\rquote  Streek was seated like the Fresh Prince of DC in one of the holding cells.  The street punk looked up at me as I entered his cell.  A slicky-sick smirk crossed his face.
\par Sneak was sporting wraparound sunglasses, dusty dreadlocks, a bright-green and yellow crocheted hat.  His white T-shirt had a drawing of Haile Selassie\rquote s face and read: HEAD HUNTER.  RASTAFARIAN.
\par \lquote You from the DA\rquote s office?   I don\rquote t think so.  No dealee, no talkee, my man,\rquote  he said to me.  \lquote So get lost.\rquote 
\par Rakeem ignored him as he talked to me.  \lquote Sneak claims to have some useful information about the Glover and Cardinal homicides.  He would like us to extend him some courtesy in return for what he claims to know.  He\rquote 
s jammed up on a charge that he may have broken into an apartment in Shaw.  He was caught coming out of a bedroom window with a Sony TV in his arms.  Imagine that.  Not very Sneaky of him.\rquote 
\par \lquote I didn\rquote t rob no ticky-tacky apartment.  I don\rquote t even watch TV, my man.  And I don\rquote t see no assistant district attorney present with the au-tho-rity to make a deal.\rquote 
\par \lquote Take off your sunglasses,\rquote  I said to him.
\par He ignored me, so I took them off for him.  As one well-known street saying goes \lquote His eyes were like tombstones.\rquote   I could tell at a glance that Sneak wasn\rquote t just running drugs anymore; he was using.
\par I stood across from Sneak in the jail cell and stared him down.  He was probably in his early twenties, angry, cynical, lost in space and time.  \lquote If you didn\rquote t rob the apartment, then why would you be int
erested in seeing a lawyer from the district attorney\rquote s office?   That doesn\rquote t make too much sense to me, Alfred.  Now here\rquote s what I\rquote ll do for you and it\rquote 
s a one-time offer, so listen carefully.  If I walk out of here, I don\rquote t come back.\rquote 
\par Sneak half-listened to what I was saying.
\par \lquote If you give us information that directly helps solve the murders of those two young girls, then we will help you on the robbery charges.  I\rquote ll go to the mat myself.  If you don\rquote t give up the information then I\rquote 
m going to leave you in here with Detective Powell and Detective Thurman.  You won\rquote t get this generous, one-time offer again.  Thats another promise, and as these detectives know, I always keep my word.\rquote 
\par Sneak still didn\rquote t say anything.  A glaze was coming over his eyes.  He tried to stare me down, but I\rquote m usually better at it than the average TV booster.
\par I finally shrugged a look at Rakeem Powell and Jerome Thurman.\rquote   Okay, fine.  Gentlemen, we need to know what he knows about those murdered girls in Shaw.  He gets nothing from us when you\rquote re finished with him.  It\rquote s possible that he
\rquote s involved with the homicides himself.  He could even be our killer, and we need to solve this thing fast.  You treat him that way until we know differently.\rquote 
\par I started to get up, when suddenly Sneak spoke.
\par \lquote Back Door Man.  He hang at Downing Park.  He, Back Door, maybe see who done those girls.  That\rquote s how he say it at the park.  Say he saw the killer.  So how you gonna help me?\rquote 
\par I walked out of the cell.  \lquote I told you the deal, Alfred.  We solve the case, your information helps, I\rquote ll help you.\rquote 
\par 
