\par Maybe we were close to something.  Two Metro cruisers and two unmarked sedans pulled up to the fenced-in entrance of tiny Downing playground in Shaw.  Rakeem Powell and Sampson went with me to visit with Joe \lquote Back Door\rquote 
 Booker, a well-known neighborhood menace.
\par I knew Back Door by sight and spotted him right away.  He was short, no more than five-seven, goateed, and so good with a basketball that he sometimes played in work boots, just 
to show off.  He had on dusty orange construction boots today.  Also a faded black nylon jacket and black nylon pants that accordioned at the ankles.
\par A full-court basketball game was in progress, a fast, high-level game, somewhere between college and pro in terms of athletic ability.  The court couldn\rquote 
t have been more basic - black macadam, faded white lines, metal backboards and rims with chain nets.
\par Players from two or three other teams sat around waiting their turn to play winners.  Nylon shorts and pants and the Nike swoosh were everywhere.  The court was surrounded by four walls of heavy wire fencing and was known as the \lquote cage\rquote 
.  Everybody looked up as we arrived, Booker included.
\par \lquote We got next!\rquote  Sampson called out.
\par The players on and off the court exchanged looks and a couple of them grinned at Sampson\rquote s one-liner.  They knew who we were.  The steady thump, thump, thump on the game ball hadn\rquote t stopped.
\par Back Door was on the court.  It wasn\rquote t unusual for his team to hold winners for an entire afternoon.  H
e had been in and out of reformatories and prisons since he was fourteen, but he could play ball.  He was taunting another player who was on the court in gray suit pants, high-tops, a bare chest, \lquote You suck,\rquote 
 said Back Door.  Take those church pants off.  I play you in baseball, tennis, bowling, any game - you suck.  Stop suckin\rquote .\rquote 
\par Rakeem Powell blew the silver referee\rquote s whistle he always carries.  Rakeem works as a soccer ref in his spare time.  The whistle is unorthodox, but it gets attention in noisy places.  The game stopped.
\par The three of us walked up to Booker, who was standing near the foul circle at one basket.  Sampson and I towered over him.  But so did most of the players.  It didn\rquote t matter, he was still the best ballplayer out there.  He could prob
ably beat Sampson and me if we played him two on one.
\par \lquote Awhh, leave the brother alone.  He didn\rquote t do nothin,\rquote  one of the other, taller men complained in a deep voice.  He had prison-style tattoos all over his back and arms.  \lquote He was here playin\rquote  ball, man.\rquote 
\par \lquote Door been here all day,\rquote  said somebody else.  \lquote Door been here for days.  Hasn\rquote t lost a game in days!\rquote 
\par Several of the young men laughed at the playground humor.  Sampson turned to the biggest man on the court.  \lquote Shut the hell up.  Stop dribbling that rock, too.  Two young sisters been murdered.  That\rquote s why we\rquote 
re here.  This is no game with us.\rquote 
\par The dribbler shut up and picked up the game ball.  The yard became strangely quiet.  We could hear a jump rope striking the sidewalk in a fast rhythm.  Three little girls playing just outside the cage were saying, \lquote 
Little Miss Pinky dressed in blue, died last night at half past two.\rquote   It was a jump-rope rhyme, sadly true around here.
\par I put my arm around Booker\rquote s shoulder and walked him away from his friends.
\par Sampson continued to do the talking.  \lquote Booker, this is going to be so fast and easy you and your friends will be laughing your asses off about it before we\rquote re back in our cars.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah, uh-huh,\rquote  said Joseph Booker, trying to be cool in the extreme heat of Sampson\rquote s and my glare.
\par \lquote I\rquote m serious as a heart attack, little man.  You saw something that can help us with the murder of Tori Glover and Marion Cardinal.  Simple as that.  You talk and we walk right back out of here.\rquote 
\par Booker glared up at Sampson as if he were staring down the sun. \lquote I didn\rquote t see shit.  Like Luki say, I been here for days.  I never lose to these sorry chumps.\rquote 
\par I held up my hand, palm out, inches from his squashed moonpie face.
\par \lquote I\rquote m on a stopwatch here, Booker, so please don\rquote t interrupt my flow.  I promise you, two minutes and we\rquote re out of here.  Now here\rquote s what\rquote 
s in it for you.  One, we go away and you gentlemen finish your game.  Two, Detectives Powell and Sampson will owe you one.  Three, a hundred dollars now for your time and trouble.  The clock is ticking,\rquote  I said.  \lquote 
Tick, tick, tick.  Easy money.\rquote 
\par He finally nodded and held out his hand.
\par \lquote I seen those two girls get picked up.  Around two, three in the mornin\rquote  on E Street.  I didn\rquote t see no driver, nobody\rquote s face or nothin\rquote .  Too dark, man.  But he
 was driving a cab.  Look like purple-and-blue gypsy.  Some-thin\rquote  like that.  Girls get into the back of the cab, drive off.\rquote 
\par \lquote Is that it?\rquote   I asked him.  \lquote I don\rquote t want to have to come back here later.  Break up your game again.\rquote 
\par Booker considered what I\rquote d said, then spoke again.  \lquote Cab driver a white man.  Seen his arm stickin\rquote  out the side window.  Ain\rquote t no white boys drivin\rquote  the night shift in Shaw, least none I seen.\rquote 
\par I nodded, waited a bit, then I smiled at the other players, \lquote Gentlemen, as you were.  Play ball.\rquote  Thump, thump, thump.  Swish.  Booker could really play ball
\par 
