\par He had been much more careful lately.  The visit to Washington by George Bayer, Famine, had been a warning, a shot over his head, and Shafer had taken it seriously.  The other players could be as dangerous as he was.  It was they who had t
aught him how to kill, not the other way round.  Famine, Conqueror, and War were not to be underestimated, especially if he wanted to win the game.
\par The day after Famine\rquote s visit, the others had informed him that Bayer had come to Washington, that he was bei
ng watched.  He supposed that was his second warning.  His activity had frightened them and now they were retaliating.  It was all part of the game.
\par After work that night, he headed to the hideaway in Eckington.  He spotted what looked like a half-dozen or so policemen canvassing the street.
\par He immediately suspected the other Horsemen.  They had turned him in, after all.  Or were they playing a mind game with him?  What were the cops doing here?
\par He parked the Jaguar several blocks away, then headed toward t
he hideaway and garage on foot.  He had to check this out.  He had on a pin-striped suit, city shirt, and tie.  He knew he looked respectable enough.  He carried a leather briefcase, and definitely looked like a businessman coming home late.
\par Two African-American policemen were doing door-to-door questioning on Uhland Terrace.  This wasn\rquote t good - the police were less than five blocks from the hideaway.
\par Why were they here?  His brain was reeling, adrenaline rushing through his nervous system like a flash flood.  Maybe this had nothing to do with him, but he couldn\rquote 
t be too careful.  He definitely suspected the other players, especially George Bayer.  But why?  Was this the way they planned to end the game, by bringing him down?
\par When the two policemen up ahead disappeared down a side street off Uhland, Shafer decided to stop at one of the brownstones where they\rquote 
d been asking questions.  It was a small risk, but he needed to know what was happening.  A couple of old men were seated on the stoop.  An ancient radio played an Orioles baseball game.
\par They ask you about some kind of trouble in the neighborhood?\rquote   Shafer asked the men in as casual a tone as he could manage.  They stopped me up the block.\rquote 
\par One of the men just stared at him, terminally pissed off, but the other one nodded and spoke up.  \lquote Sure did, mister.  Lookin\rquote  for a cab, purple-and-blue gypsy.  Connected to some killings, they say.  Though I don\rquote 
t recall seeing any purple ones lately.  Used to be a cab company called Vanity.  You remember, Earl?  They had the purple people-eaters.\rquote 
\par \lquote That was some years ago,\rquote  the other man said, nodding.  They went belly up.\rquote 
\par \lquote I guess they were Metro police.  Never showed me any ID, though,\rquote  Shafer said, and shrugged.  He was being careful to speak with an American accent, which he was good at imitating.
\par \lquote Detectives Cross and Sampson.\rquote   The more talkative of the two men volunteered their names.  \lquote Detective Cross showed me his badge.  It was the real deal.\rquote 
\par \lquote Oh, I\rquote m sure it was,\rquote  Shafer said, and saluted the two old men.  "Good to see the police in the neighborhood, actually.\rquote 
\par \lquote You got that right.\rquote 
\par \lquote Have a nice night.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah, you too.\rquote 
\par Shafer circled back to his car, and drove to the embassy.  He went straight to his office, where he felt safe and protected.  He calmed himse
lf, then turned on his computer and did a thorough search on DC detectives named Cross and Sampson.  He found more than he hoped for, especially on Detective Cross.
\par He thought about how the new developments might change the game.  Then he sent out a message to the Horsemen.  He told them about Cross and Sampson -that the detectives had decided to \lquote play the game\rquote 
.  So, naturally, he had plans for them too.
