\par Zachary Scott Taylor was a thorough, analytical, and very hard-nosed reporter o
n the Washington Post.  I respected the hell out of him.  His relentless cynicism and skepticism were a little too much for me to take on a daily basis; otherwise we might have been even closer friends.  But we had a good relationship and I trusted him mo
re than I did most journalists.
\par I met him that night at the Irish Times, on F Street, near Union Station.  The restaurant-bar is in an anachronistic stand-alone brick building surrounded by modern office structures.  Zachary called it \lquote a dumpy little toilet
 of a bar, a perfect place for us to meet\rquote .
\par In the time-honored tradition of Washington, I have occasionally been one of his trusted sources, and I was about to tell the reporter something important.  I hoped he would agree, and that he could convince his editors at the Post about the story.
\par \lquote How\rquote re Master Damon and Ms. Jannie?\rquote   Zachary asked as he sat across from me in a darkened comer under an old photo of a stern-looking man in a black top hat.  Zachary is tall, gaunt and thin; he resembles the man in t
he old photo a little bit.  Zachary always talks too fast - with the words running into one another -How\rquote reMasterDamonandMsJannie?  There was just a hint of Virginia softening his accent.
\par The waitress eventually came over to our table.  He ordered black coffee and I had the same.
\par \lquote Two coffees?\rquote   she asked, to make sure she\rquote d heard us right.
\par \lquote Two of your very finest coffees,\rquote  Zachary said.
\par \lquote This isn\rquote t Starbucks, y\rquote know.\rquote   she said.
\par I smiled at the waitress\rquote s joke, then at what Zachary had said - his first words to me.  I\rquote d probably mentioned my kids\rquote  names to him once, but he had an encyclopedic memory for all kinds of disparate information.
\par \lquote You should go get yourself a couple of kids, Zachary,\rquote  I told him, smiling broadly.
\par He glanced up at an ancient whirring ceiling fan that looked as if it might suddenly spin out of the ceiling, it seemed a nice metaphor for modern life in America, an aging infrastructure threatening to spin out of control.
\par \lquote Don\rquote t have a wife yet, Alex.  Still looking for the right woman,\rquote  said Zachary.
\par \lquote Well, okay then, get yourself a wife first, then get a couple of kids.  Might take the edge off your neuroses.\rquote 
\par The waitress placed steaming cups of black coffee in front of us.  \lquote Will that be all?\rquote  she said.  She shook her head, then left us.
\par \lquote Maybe I don\rquote t want the edge taken off my rather stunning neurotic behavior.  Maybe I believe that\rquote s what makes me such a damn fine reporter, and that without it my work would be pedestrian shit, and then I\rquote 
d be nothing in the eyes of Don Graham and company.\rquote 
\par I sipped the day-or-two-old coffee.  \lquote Except that if you had a couple of kids, you could never be nothing.\rquote 
\par Zachary squinted one eye shut and smacked the left side of his lips.  He was a very animated thinker.
\par \lquote Except if the kids didn\rquote t love, or even like me very much.\rquote 
\par \lquote And you don\rquote t consider yourself lovable?  But actually you are, Zachary.  Trust me.  You\rquote re just fine.  Your kids would adore the hell out of you and you would adore them.  You\rquote d have a mutual adoration society.\rquote 
\par He finally laughed and clapped his hands loudly.  We usually laugh a good bit when we\rquote re together.
\par \lquote So will you marry me and have my children?\rquote   He grinned at me over the top of his steaming cup.  This is a pick-up joint, after all.  Singles from the Bureau of Labor Statisti
cs and the Government Printing Office come here, hoping to bed a staffer from Kennedy\rquote s or Glenn\rquote s.\rquote 
\par \lquote Actually, it\rquote s  the best offer I\rquote ve had all day.  Who called this meeting anyway?  Why are we here at this dive, drinking really bad coffee?\rquote 
\par Taylor slurped his.  \lquote Coffee\rquote s fairly strong, isn\rquote t it?  That\rquote s something to be thankful for.  What\rquote s up, Alex?\rquote 
\par \lquote You interested in another Pulitzer?\rquote  I asked him.
\par He pretended to think it over, but his eyes lit up.  \lquote Well, I might be.  You see, I need to balance the look of my mantelpiece.  One of my dates told me that.  Never did see the young woman again.  She worked for Gingrich, as a matter of fact.
\rquote 
\par For the next forty-five minutes or so, I told Zachary exactly what I thought was up.  I told him about one hundred 
and fourteen unsolved murders in Southeast and parts of Northeast DC.  I detailed the contrasting investigation of the cases of Frank Odenkirk and the German tourist in Georgetown, and the black teenagers Tori Glover and Marion Cardinal.  I filled him in 
on the chief of detectives, his proclivities and his biases, at least my perception of them.  I even admitted that I disliked Pittman intensely, and Zachary knows I\rquote m not that way about too many folks who don\rquote t murder for a living.
\par He shook his head back and forth, back and forth, while I talked, and didn\rquote t stop when I was finished.  \lquote It\rquote s not that I doubt any of what you\rquote re saying, but do you have any documentation?\rquote   he asked.
\par \lquote You\rquote re such a stickler for details,\rquote  I said.  \lquote Reporters are such wusses when you come right down to it.\rquote 
\par I reached down under my seat and lifted up two thick manila folders.  His eyes brightened.
\par This should help with the story.  Copies of sixty-seven of the unsolved homicide reports.  Also a copy of the Glover and Cardinal investigation.  Note the number of detectives assigned to each.  Check the case hours logged.
\par You\rquote ll see a huge discrepancy.  That\rquote s all I could get my hands on - but the other reports exist.\rquote 
\par \lquote Why would this be happening, this malicious neglect?\rquote  he asked me.
\par I nodded at the wisdom of his question.  \lquote I\rquote ll give you the most cynical reason,\rquote  I said.  \lquote 
Some Metro cops like to refer to Southeast as "self-cleaning ovens".  That sound like the beginnings of malicious neglect to you?  Some victims in Southeast are called NHIs - that\rquote s No Humans Involved.  The latter is a phrase used by Chief Pittman.
\rquote 
\par Zachary quickly leafed through the reports.  Then he shook my hand.  I\rquote m going home to my lonely abode, made bearable only by my single Pulitzer.  I have all these fascinati
ng police files on NHIs to read, then hopefully a chilling news expose to write.  We\rquote ll see.  As always, it\rquote s been a party, Alex.  My best to Damon, Jannie, Nana Mama.  I\rquote d like to meet them one day.  Put some faces with the names.
\rquote 
\par \lquote Come to the next Washington Boys\rquote  Choir performance.\rquote  I said.  \lquote All our faces will be there.  Damon is a chorister.\rquote 
\par 
