\par I worked that night until eight thirty, and then I drove to Kinkead\rquote s in Foggy Bottom to meet up with Christine.  Kinkead\rquote s is one of our favorite restaurants and also an excellent place to listen to jazz, and snuggle up to each other.

\par I sat at the bar and enjoyed the sounds of Hilton Felton and Ephrain Woolfolk until Christine arrived, coming from an event at school.  She was right on time
, though.  She is punctual.  Very considerate.  Perfect in almost every way, at least in my eyes.  Yes, I will be your wife.
\par \lquote You hungry?  Want to go to a table?\rquote   I asked, after we had hugged as if we\rquote d been separated for many years and thousands of miles.
\par \lquote Let\rquote s just sit here at the bar for a few minutes.  You mind?\rquote   she asked.  Her breath smelled lightly of spearmint.  Her face was so soft and smooth that I had to lightly cup it in both my hands.
\par \lquote Nothing I\rquote d rather do in the whole wide world,\rquote  I said.
\par Christine ordered a Harvey\rquote s Bristol Cream and I had a mug of beer, and we talked as the music flowed over, around, and right through our bodies.  It had been a long day, and I needed this.
\par I\rquote ve been waiting for this all day long.  I couldn\rquote t wait.  Am I being too corny and romantic again?\rquote   I said, and grinned.
\par \lquote Not for me.  Never too corny, never too romantic.  That won\rquote t happen, Alex.\rquote   Christine smiled.  I loved to see her like this.  Her eyes twinkled and danced.  I sometimes get lost in her eyes, fall
 into the deep pools, all that good stuff that people yearn for but few seem to get nowadays, which is sad.
\par She stared back and my fingers lightly caressed her cheek.  Then I held her under her chin.  \lquote Stardust was playing.  It\rquote s one of my favorite songs, 
even under ordinary circumstances.  I wondered if Hilton and Ephrain were playing the tune for us, and when I looked at him, Hilton gave me a sly wink.
\par We moved closer together and danced in place.  I could feel her heart beating; feel it right up against 
my chest.  We must have stayed like that for ten or fifteen minutes.  No one at the bar seemed to notice; no one bothered us -offered to refill our drinks, or escort us to our table.  I guess they understood.
\par \lquote I really like Kinkead\rquote s.\rquote   Christine whispered.  \lquote But you know what?  I\rquote d rather be home with you tonight.  Some place a little more private.  I\rquote ll make you eggs, whatever you\rquote 
d like.  Is that all right?  Do you mind?\rquote   \lquote No, I don\rquote t mind at all.  That\rquote s a perfect idea.  Lets go.\rquote   I paid our bar bill, made my regrets about the dinner reservation.  Then we went to Christine\rquote s.  \lquote 
We\rquote ll start with dessert.\rquote   she said and smiled wickedly.
\par I liked that about her too.
