\par Much later that night we rustled up some eggs with Vidalia onions and cheddar and mozzarella cheeses, opened a nice bottle of Pinot Noir.  Then I started a fire, in August, with the air-conditioner turned up high.
\par We sat in front of the fire, laughed and talked, and planned a quick trip away from Washington.  We settled on Bermuda, and Christine asked
 if we could bring Nana and the kids.  I felt as if my life were changing fast, going to a new good place.  If only I could get lucky and catch the Weasel somehow.  That could be the perfect ending to my career with the Metro police.
\par I went home to Fifth Street late, got in just before three.  I didn\rquote t want Damon and Jannie to wake in the morning and not find me there.  I was up by eight o\rquote 
clock the next morning, bounding downstairs to the delectable smells of fresh coffee and Nana\rquote s world-famous sticky buns.
\par The terrible twosome were just about ready to dash off to the Sojourner Truth School where they were taking advanced classes in the morning.  They looked like a pair of shiny angels.  I didn\rquote 
t get to feel this good very often, so I was going all the way with it.
\par \lquote How was your date last night, Daddy?\rquote   Jannie said, making her biggest goo-goo eyes at me.
\par \lquote Who said I had a date?\rquote   I made room for her on my knee.  She ate a bite of the humongous sweet bun Nana had set on my plate.
\par \lquote Let\rquote s just say a little birdie told me,\rquote  she chirped.
\par \lquote Uh-huh.  Little birdie makes good sticky buns,\rquote  I said.  \lquote My date was pretty good.  How was yours?  You had a date, right?  Didn\rquote t sit home alone, did you?\rquote 
\par \lquote Your date was pretty good?  You came home with the milkman.\rquote   Jannie laughed out loud.  Damon was giggling, too.  She can get us all going when she wants to; she\rquote s been that way since she was a baby.
\par \lquote Jannie Cross.\rquote   Nana said, but she let it go.  There was no use trying to make Jannie act like a typical seven-year-old at t
his point.  She was too bright, too outspoken, too full of life and fun.  Besides, we have a philosophy as a family: he or she who laughs, lasts.
\par \lquote How come you two don\rquote t live together first?\rquote   Jannie asked.  That\rquote s what they all do in the movies and on TV.\rquote 
\par I found myself grinning and starting to frown at the same time.  \lquote Don\rquote t get me going on the silly stuff they do on TV and in the movies, little girl.  They always get it wrong.  Christine and I are going to get married soon, and then we
\rquote ll all live together.\rquote 
\par \lquote You sure you asked her?\rquote   they all exclaimed.
\par \lquote I did.\rquote 
\par \lquote And she said yes?\rquote 
\par \lquote Why do you all look so surprised?  Of course she said yes.  Who could resist being a part of this family?\rquote 
\par \lquote Hooray!\rquote   Jannie whooped loudly.  I could tell she meant it from the bottom of her little heart.
\par \lquote Hooray!\rquote   echoed Nana.  \lquote Thank God.  Oh, thank God.\rquote 
\par \lquote I agree.\rquote   Damon piped in.  \lquote It\rquote s  time that we had a more normal life around here.\rquote 
\par Everybody was congratulating me for several minutes until Jannie finally said, \lquote I have to go to school now, Pa-pa.  I wouldn\rquote t want to disappoint Ms. Johnson by being late, now would I?  \lquote Here\rquote s your morning newspaper.\rquote 

\par Jannie handed me the Washington Post and my heart jumped a little in my chest.  This was a good day indeed.  I saw Zachary Taylor\rquote s story in the bottom right of the front page.  It wasn\rquote t the banner headline it deserved to be, but he\rquote 
d gotten the story on page one.
\par Potential scandal over unsolved murders in Southeast DC.  Possible racial bias seen in police activity.
\par \lquote Potential scandal indeed,\rquote  Nana said, and squeegeed her lower face.  \lquote Genocide always is, isn\rquote t it?\rquote 
