\par I entered the station house around nine and Chief Pittman\rquote s assistant-lackey came scurrying up to me.  Old Fred Cook had been a bad detecti
ve once, and now was an equally bad and devious administrator, but Fred was as smooth a buttkisser as could be found in the department or anywhere else in Washington.
\par \lquote The chief of detectives wants to see you in his office, post-haste.  It\rquote s important.\rquote   Fred told me.  \lquote Better move it.\rquote 
\par I nodded at him and tried to keep my good mood intact.  \lquote Of course it is, he\rquote s the chief of detectives.  You have any helpful hints for me, Fred?  You happen to know what this is about, what I should expect?\rquote 
\par \lquote It\rquote s a big deal,\rquote  said Cook, unhelpful and happy about it.  \lquote That\rquote s about all I can tell you, Alex.\rquote 
\par He walked away, leaving me hanging.  I could feel the bile rising in my throat.  My good mood had already deserted me.
\par I walked down the creaking hardwood floors of the hallway to the Jefe\rquote s office.  I had no idea what to expect; but I sure wasn\rquote t prepared for what I found.
\par I immediately thought about what Damon had said that morning: It\rquote s time that we had a more normal life around here.
\par Sampson was seated inside the chief\rquote s office.  Rakeem Powell and Jerome Thurman were both in there, too.
\par \lquote Come in, Dr. Cross.\rquote   Chief Pittman beckoned with an outstretched hand.  \lquote Please come in.  We\rquote ve been waiting for you to arrive.\rquote 
\par \lquote What is this?\rquote   I said, pulling up a chair next to Sampson\rquote s, whispering in his ear.
\par \lquote Don\rquote t know yet, but it\rquote s not too good,\rquote  he said.  The Jefe hasn\rquote t said one word to us.  Looks like the canary who ate the cat, though.\rquote 
\par Pittman came around in front of his desk and leaned his ample buttocks back against it.  He seemed particularly full of himself, and shit, this morning.  His mousy gray hair was plastered back and looked like a helmet on his bullet head.
\par \lquote I can tell you what you want to know, Detective Cross.\rquote   he said.  \lquote In fact, I didn\rquote t want to tell these
 other detectives until you got here.  As of this morning, Detectives Sampson, Thurman, and Powell have been suspended from active duty.  They have been working on cases outside the auspices of this department.  Evidence is still being gathered about the 
full extent of these activities; and also, if any other detectives were involved.\rquote 
\par I started to speak up, but Sampson grabbed my arm -hard.  \lquote Be cool, Alex.\rquote 
\par Pittman looked at the three of them.  \lquote Detectives Sampson, Thurman, Powell, you can go.  Your union representative has been informed of the situation.  You have questions, or issues with my decision, inform your representative.\rquote 
\par Sampson\rquote s mouth was set hard.  He didn\rquote t say a word to the Jefe, though.  He got up and left the office.  Thurman and Powell t
railed close behind him.  Neither of them spoke to Pittman either.  The three of them were hardworking, dedicated detectives, and I couldn\rquote t stand to watch this happen.
\par I wondered why the Jefe had spared me so far.  I also wondered why Shawn Moore wasn\rquote t there.  The cynical answer was that Pittman wanted to set us against one another, to make us believe that Shawn had spoken against us.
\par Pittman reached across his desk and picked up a folded copy of the Washington Post.  \lquote You happen to see this article today?  Bottom right?\rquote 
\par He pushed the newspaper toward me.  I had to catch the paper to keep it from falling to the floor.
\par \lquote Scandal over unsolved murders in Southeast,\rquote  I said.  \lquote Yes, I did.  I read it at home.\rquote 
\par \lquote I\rquote ll bet you did.  Mr. Taylor, of the Post, quotes unidentified sources in the police department.  You have anything to do with the article?\rquote   Pittman asked and stared hard at me.
\par \lquote Why would I talk to the Washington Post?\rquote   I asked a question in answer to his.  \lquote I told you about the problem in Southeast.
  I think a repeat killer may be working there.  Why go any farther with it than that?  Suspending those detectives sure won\rquote t help solve the problem.  Especially if this sicko is approaching rage, which I believe he is.\rquote 
\par \lquote I don\rquote t buy this serial-killer story.  I don\rquote t see any pattern that\rquote s consistent.  No one else does but you.\rquote   Pittman shook his head and frowned.  He was hot, angry, trying to control himself.
\par He reached out his hand toward me again.  His fingers were like uncooked sausages.  He lowered his voice almost to a whisper.  \lquote I\rquote d like to fuck you over good, and I will.  But for now, it wouldn\rquote 
t be expedient to pull you off the Odenkirk homicide.  It wouldn\rquote t look good, and I suspect it would end up in the Post, too.  I look forward to your daily
 reports on the so-called John Doe case.  You know, it is time you got some of those unsolved murders off the books.  You\rquote ll report directly to me on this.  I\rquote m going to be all over you, Cross.  Any questions?\rquote 
\par I quickly left Chief Pittman\rquote s office.  Before I hit him.
