\par Sampson, Thurman, and Rakeem Powell had already left the building by the time I got out of the Jefe\rquote s office.  I felt as if I could easily go postal.  I nearly walked back inside Pittman\rquote s office and wiped up the floor with him.
\par I went to my desk and thought about what to do next, tried to calm myself down before I did anything rash and stupid.  I thought about my responsibilities to the people in Southeast and that helped me.  Still, I almost went back after Pittman.
\par I cal
led Christine and let out some steam.  Then, spur of the moment, I asked if she could get away for our long weekend, possibly starting on Thursday night.  Christine said that she could go.  I went and filled out a vacation form and left it on Fred Cook
\rquote s desk.  It was the last thing he and Pittman would expect from me.  But I\rquote d already decided the best thing would be to get away from here, cool down, then decide on a plan to move forward.
\par As I headed out of the building, another detective stopped me.  They\rquote re over at Hart\rquote s bar,\rquote  he said.  \lquote Sampson said to tell you they reserved a seat for you.\rquote 
\par Hart\rquote s is a very seedy, very popular gin mill on Second Street.  It isn\rquote t a cops\rquote  bar, which is why some of us like it.  It was eleven in the morning and the bar room was already crowded, lively, even friendly.
\par \lquote Here he is!\rquote   Jerome Thurman saluted me with a half-full beer mug as I walked inside.  Half-a-dozen other detectives and friends were there, too.  The word had gotten around fast about the suspensions.
\par There was a whole lot of laughter and shouting going on.  \lquote It\rquote s a bachelor\rquote s party!\rquote   Sampson said, and grinned.  \lquote Got you, sugar.  With a little help from Nana.  You should see the look on your face!\rquote 
