\par It took us a day to get organized for our trip, but everybody seemed to enjoy the spontaneity, and also the special trea
t that we would all be together on a vacation for the first time.  And so, Damon, Jannie, Nana, Christine, and I left DC in the afternoon and arrived in high spirits at Bermuda International Airport late on Thursday evening, the twenty-fifth of August.

\par I definitely wanted to be out of Washington for a few days.  The Mr. Smith murder case had been followed too quickly by the Jane Doe investigation.  I needed a rest.  I had a friend who was part owner of a hotel in Bermuda, and it wasn\rquote 
t a particularly long airplane ride.  It was perfect for us.
\par One scene from the airport will always stick in my mind - Christine singing \lquote Ja-da, ja-da\rquote  with Jannie stuck at her side.  I couldn\rquote t help thinking that they looked like mother and daughter and that touched me deeply. 
 They were so affectionate and playful, so natural.  It was a mind-photo for me to have and to hold.  One of those moments that I knew I\rquote d never forget, even as I watched the two of them dancing and singing as if they\rquote 
d known each other forever.
\par We were bl
essed with extraordinarily good weather for our holiday.  It was sunny and blue-skied every day, morning until nightfall, when the sky turned a magical combination of reds, oranges, and purples.  The days belonged to all of us, but especially the kids.  W
e went swimming and snorkeling at Elbow Beach and Horseshoe Bay, and then raced mopeds along the picturesque Middle and Harbor Roads.
\par The nights belonged to Christine and me, and we made the most of them.  We hit all the best spots: the Terrace Bar at the P
alm Reef, the Gazebo Lounge at the Princess, the Clay House Inn, Once Upon a Table in Hamilton, Horizons in Paget.  I loved being with her and that thought kept drifting through my mind.  I felt that what we shared had been strengthened because I had back
ed off and given her time and space.  And I felt whole again.  I kept remembering the very first time I had seen her in the schoolyard at Sojourner Truth.  She\rquote s the one, Alex.  That thought still played in my head too.
\par We sat at the Terrace Bar overlooking the city and harbor of Hamilton.  It was dotted with small islands, white sails, ferries back and forth to Warwick and Paget.  We held hands and I couldn\rquote t stop staring into her eyes, didn\rquote t want to.

\par \lquote Big thoughts\rquote  she finally said.
\par \lquote I\rquote ve been thinking a lot about going into private practice again,\rquote  I told her.  \lquote I think it might be the best thing to do.\rquote 
\par She stared into my eyes.  \lquote I don\rquote t want you to do it for me, Alex.  Please don\rquote t make me the cause of your leaving your job with the police.  I know you love it.  Most days you do.\rquote 
\par \lquote The job has been tearing at me lately.  Pittman isn\rquote t just a difficult boss, I think he\rquote s a bad guy.  What happened to Sampson and the others is just bullshit.  They were working unsolved cases on their own time.  I\rquote m tempted 
to give the story to Zach Taylor at the Post.  People would riot if they knew the truth.  Which is why I won\rquote t give it to the Post.\rquote 
\par She listened and tried to help but she didn\rquote t push, and I appreciated that.  \lquote It does sound like a terrible, complicated, nasty mess, Alex.  I\rquote d like to punch out Pittman, too.  He\rquote s choosing politics over protecting people.  I
\rquote m sure you\rquote ll know what to do when the time is right.\rquote 
\par The next morning, I found her walking in the garden, with tropical flowers strewn in her hair.  She looked radiant, even more than usual, and I fell in love all over again.
\par \lquote There\rquote s an old saying I\rquote ve been hearing since I was a little girl,\rquote  she told me as I joined her.  \lquote If you have only two pennies, buy a loaf of bread with one, and a lily with the other.\rquote 
\par I kissed her hair, in between the flowers.  I kissed her sweet lips, her cheeks, the hollow in her throat.
\par The kids and I went back to Horseshoe Bay beach early that afternoon.  They couldn\rquote t get enough of the deep blue sea, swimming, snorkeling, 
building sand castles, and of course it was almost time to start school again so everything about our vacation was extra special and intense.
\par Christine took a moped trip into Hamilton to pick up mementos for a few of the teachers at Sojourner Truth.  We all waved until she was out of sight on Middle Road.  Then back into the water!
\par Around five o\rquote clock, Damon, Jannie, and I finally returned to the Belmont Hotel, which sat like a sentinel on lush green hills framed by china-blue skies.  All around, everywhere
 we looked, were pastel-colored cottages with white roofs.  Nana was sitting out on the porch, talking to a couple of her new best friends.  Paradise regained, I thought, and felt something deep and sacred coming back to life inside me.
\par As I stared out at the cloudless blue sky, I regretted that Christine wasn\rquote 
t there to share it.  I actually missed her in just that short a time.  I hugged Jannie and Damon and we were all smiling at the obvious.  We loved being here together and we were so damn fortunate to have one another.
