\par Inspector Stride Busby from the Hamilton PD arrived at the Belmont Hotel around seven thirty.  He was a small, balding man and from a distance he looked to be in his late fifties or sixties.  As he approache
d the front porch, I could tell he was no more than forty, around the same age as me.
\par He listened to my story, then said that visitors often lost track of time and themselves in Bermuda.  There were also occasional moped accidents on the Middle Road.  He promised me that Christine would show up soon with a \lquote mild road rash\rquote 
, or a \lquote slightly turned ankle\rquote .
\par I wouldn\rquote t have any of it.  She was always punctual, or at the very least, she would have called.
\par I knew that somehow she\rquote d call if she had a minor accident
.  So the inspector and I rode together between the hotel and Hamilton, and then we toured the streets of the capital city, particularly Front and Reid Streets.  I was silent and solemn-faced as I stared out of the car, hoping to get a glimpse of Christin
e shopping on some side street, forgetful of the hour.  But we didn\rquote t see her anywhere, and she still hadn\rquote t called the hotel.
\par When she hadn\rquote t turned up by nine, Inspector Busby reluctantly agreed that Christine might be missing.  He asked a lot of questions that showed me he was a decent cop.  He wanted to know if we\rquote d had any kind of argument or disagreement.

\par \lquote I\rquote m a homicide detective in Washington, DC,\rquote  I finally told him.  I\rquote d been holding it back because I didn\rquote t want this to get territorial.  \lquote I\rquote ve bee
n involved with high-profile cases involving mass murders in the past.  I\rquote ve known some very bad men.  There might be a connection.  I hope not, but that could be.\rquote 
\par \lquote I see,\rquote  Busby said.  He was such a precise, neat man, with his thin pencil mustache.  He looked more like a fussy schoolteacher than a cop, more like a psychologist than I did.  \lquote 
Are there any other surprises I should know about, Detective Cross?\rquote   he asked.
