\par I exploded out the back kitchen door without saying a word to Nana or the kids.  I didn\rquote t have time to explain where I was going, or why.  Besides, I didn\rquote t really know exactly what was happening.  Had I just spoken to the Weasel?
\par I\rquote m serious.  Hurry!  Maybe she\rquote s on the pay phone right now!
\par I sprinted across Fifth Street, then down a side alley and over to Fourth.  I dashed another four blocks south toward the Anacostia River.  People on the streets watched me running.  I was like a tornado suddenly roaring through Southeast.
\par I could see the metal frame of a pay phone from more than a block away as I approached Budget Drugs.  A young girl was leaning against the graffiti-covered wall of the drugstore, talking on the phone.
\par I pulled out my detective\rquote s shield as I raced the final block toward her.
\par The phone gets a lot of use.  Some people don\rquote t have phones in their homes in the neighborhood.
\par \lquote Police.  I\rquote m a homicide detective.  Get off the phone!\rquote   I told the girl, who looked nineteen or so.  She stared at me as if she couldn\rquote t care less that a DC policeman was trying to commandeer the phone.
\par \lquote I\rquote m using this phone, mister.  Don\rquote t care who you are.  You can wait your turn like everybody else.\rquote   She turned away from me.  \lquote Probably just calling your honey.\rquote 
\par I yanked the receiver away from her, disconnected her call.
\par \lquote The fuck you think you are!\rquote   the girl shouted at me, her face screwed in anger.  \lquote I was talking.  The fuck you thinking.\rquote 
