\par \lquote I hope not, but you may be right.\rquote 
\par I glanced around at the lower-middle-class neighborhood as we walked.  Overhead, the sky was a bright-blue canvas, nearly empty of clouds.  T
he street was packed with one- and two-story homes.  Bright orange fliers were sticking out from the mailboxes.  Every window was a possible lookout for the Weasel.  Back away, he had warned.  I couldn\rquote t.  Not after what he\rquote 
d done.  I knew that I was taking a risk though.
\par He probably spotted us canvassing the streets.  If he was responsible for the Jane Doe murders, he had been working undetected for a long while.  He was skillful, good at killing, at not getting caught.
\par The landlady told us what she knew about Arthur Marshall, which wasn\rquote 
t much more than the information she needed to rent him a one-bedroom apartment and the attached garage.  She gave us a set of keys for the place and said we could go look for ourselves.
\par The second house was similar to the landlady\rquote s except that it was painted Easter-egg blue.  Sampson and I entered the garage first.
\par The purple-and-blue cab was there.
\par Arthur Marshall had told the landlady that he owned the cab and operated it as a part-time job.  That was a possibility, but 
it seemed unlikely.  The Weasel was close.  I could feel it now.  Had he known we would find the cab?  Probably.  Now what?  What came next?  What was his plan?  His fantasy?
\par \lquote I\rquote m going to have to figure out how to get some techies in here,\rquote  I told Sampson.  There has to be something in the cab, or maybe upstairs in the apartment.  Hair, fibers, prints.\rquote 
\par \lquote Hopefully no damn body parts,\rquote  Sampson said, and grimaced.  It was typical cop humor, and so automatic that I didn\rquote t give it a second thought.  \lquote Body parts are always popping up in these cases, Alex.  I don\rquote 
t want to see it.  I like feet attached to ankles, heads attached to necks, even if all the parts happen to be dead.\rquote 
\par Sampson searched around the front seat of the cab, with latex-gloved hands.  \lquote Papers in here.  Candy and gum wrappers, too.  Why not call in a favor from Kyle Craig?  Get the FBI boys over here.\rquote 
\par \lquote Actually, I talked to Kyle last night,\rquote  I said.  \lquote The Bureau\rquote s been involved for some time.  He\rquote ll help out if we say the word.\rquote 
\par Sampson tossed me a pair of gloves and I examined the cab\rquote s backseat.  I saw what could be bloodstains in the fabric of the seat cushion.  The stains would be easy enough to check out.
\par John and I finally climbed upstairs into the apartment above the garage.  It was dusty, grimy, without much furniture.  Eerie and unpleasant on the eyes.  It didn\rquote 
t look as if anyone lived there, but if someone did, they were really weird.  The landlady had said as much.
\par The kitchen was mostly empty.  An expensive juicer was the only person
al indulgence.  Not a low-end model -expensive.  I took out my handkerchief and opened the refrigerator.  There was nothing in it but bottled water and some aging fruit.  The fruit was rotting and I hated to think of what else we might find here in the ap
artment.
\par \lquote Health nut,\rquote  Sampson offered.
\par \lquote Nut anyway.\rquote   I said.  \lquote There\rquote s a sense of animal fear in here.  He gets very tense, excited, when he comes to this place.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeah.\rquote   Sampson said, \lquote I know the feeling.\rquote 
\par We entered the bedroom, which had a small cot, a couple of stuffed chairs, nothing else.  The sense of fear was here, too.
\par I opened the closet door and what I saw stopped me dead.  There was a pair of khaki pants, a blue chambray shirt, a blue blazer - and something else.
\par \lquote John, come here.\rquote   I called.  \lquote John!\rquote 
\par \lquote Oh, shit.  Do I have to?  Not more bodies.\rquote 
\par \lquote Just come here.  It\rquote s him.  This is the Weasel\rquote s place.  I\rquote m sure of it.  It\rquote s worse than a body.\rquote 
\par I opened the closet door wider and let Sampson see what I\rquote d found there.
\par \lquote Shit.\rquote   he groaned.  \lquote Goddamn it, Alex.\rquote 
\par Someone had put up pictures.  Half-a-dozen black-and-white photographs were taped to the wall of the closet.  It wasn\rquote t a killer\rquote s shrine.  It was meant to be found.
\par There were pictures of Nana, Damon, Jannie, me, and Christine.  Christine almost seemed to be smiling at the camera, that incredible smile of hers, those big welcoming eyes.
\par The pictures had been taken in Bermuda.  Whoever had rented this apartment had taken them.  Finally, I had something to link Christine\rquote s abduction to the murders in Washington.  I knew who had taken her.
\par Back off.
\par Before you lose everything.
\par I sensed fear again.  It was my own.
