\par Patsy Hampton had decided that she wasn\rquote t ready to confide in Chief George Pittman just yet.  She didn\rquote t want the Jefe interfering or crowding her.  Also, she flat out didn\rquote t trust or like the bastard.
\par She still hadn\rquote t made up her mind what to do about Alex Cross.  Cross was a complication.  The more she checked him out, the better he looked.  He seemed to be a very good, dedicated detective and she felt bad about keeping Chuck Hufstedler\rquote 
s information away from him.  Chuck had been Cross\rquote s source first, but she\rquote d used the techie\rquote s crush on her to gain an advantage.  She didn\rquote t like herself for doing that.
\par She drove her Jeep to the British Embassy late that afternoon.  She had Geoffrey Shafer under limited surveillance - hers.  She could get more teams, but that would mean going to Pittman now, and she didn\rquote 
t want anyone to know what she had.  She didn\rquote t want to be crowded.
\par She had done preliminary homework on Shafer.  He was in the Security Service, which meant he was British Intelligence, operating outside England.  Most likely he was a spy working out of the embassy on Massachusetts Avenue.  His reputation was okay, g
ood, actually.  His current assignment supposedly had to do with the British Government\rquote s human-rights program, which meant the assignment was bullshit.  He lived in Kalorama, and that was a high-rent district he shouldn\rquote 
t be able to afford on his salary.  So, who the hell was this Shafer chap?
\par Hampton sat parked in her vehicle outside the embassy on California Street.  She smoked a Marlboro Light and started to think things through.  She really ought to talk to Cross about where he was with his investigati
on.  Did he know anything that could help?  Maybe he was onto Shafer?  It was almost criminal for her not to contact Cross and share what she\rquote d gotten from Chucky Cheese.
\par Pittman\rquote s dislike for Cross was well-known; he considered him competition.  She didn\rquote 
t know Cross that well, but he got too many headlines.  Still, she wished she knew what Cross had in his files, and especially if Geoffrey Shafer might have appeared on Cross\rquote s radar.
\par There was too much fricking noise on the fricking street near the Britis
h Embassy.  Workers were doing construction on the Turkish Chancery across California Street.  Hampton already had a headache - her life was one big headache - and she wished they would stop pounding and hammering and battering and sawing.  For some reaso
n or other, there was a crowd of people swarming all over the National Mosque today.
\par At a few minutes past five Shafer got into his Jaguar in a parking lot outside the glass-walled Rotunda.
\par She\rquote d seen him twice before and he was in very good shape.  Attractive, too, though not a physical type she herself responded to.  Shafer sure didn\rquote 
t hang around long after the workday ended.  Hampton figured he either had some place to go or he really hated his day job.  Possibly both.
\par She stayed a safe distance behind the black Jag, following it along crowded Massachusetts Avenue.  Shafer didn\rquote t seem to be heading home, and he wasn\rquote t going to Southeast either.
\par Where are we going tonight?  She wondered as she tailed him.  And what does it have to do with The Four Horsemen?  What game are you really playing?  What are your fantasies?
\par Are you a bad man, a murderer, Geoffrey?  You don\rquote t look like it, Blondie.  Such a nice spiffy car for a scumbag killer.
\par 
