\par After work, Geoffrey Shafer joined the clogged artery of rush-hour traffic inching along Massachusetts.  Turning out of the embassy he had spotted the black Jeep behind him.
\par The tail was still there as he drove down Massachusetts Avenue.
\par Who was in the Jeep?  One of the other players?  DC police?  Detective Alex Cross?  They had found the garage in Eckington.  Now they\rquote d found him.  It had to be the bloody police.
\par He watched the black Jeep as it trailed four cars behind him.  There was only one person inside and it looked like a woman.  Could it possibly be Lucy?  Had she discovered the truth about him?  God, had she finally figured out who and what he was?
\par He picked up his mobile phone and made a call home.  Lucy picked up after a couple of rings.
\par \lquote Darling, I\rquote m coming home, after all.  There\rquote s a bit of a lull at the office.  We can order in or something - unless you and the children already have plans.\rquote 
\par She blathered on in the usual maddening way.  She and the twins had been going to see a movie, Ante, but they\rquote d rather stay at home with him.  They could order from Pizza Hut.  It would be fun for a change.
\par \lquote Yes, what fun,\rquote  Shafer said, and cringed at the thought.  Pizza Hut served indigestible cardboard drenched with very bad tomato soup.  He hung up, then took a couple of Vicodin and a Xanax.  He thought he
 could feel cracks slowly opening up in his skull.
\par He made a dangerous U-turn on Massachusetts Avenue and headed toward home.  He passed the Jeep going in the opposite direction and was tempted to wave.  A woman driver.  Now, who was she?
\par The pizza got to 
the house at around seven and Shafer opened an expensive bottle of Cabernet Sauvignon.  He washed down another Xanax with the wine in the downstairs bathroom.  Felt a little confused, fuzzy around the edges.  That was all right, he supposed.
\par Jesus Christ, he couldn\rquote t stand being with his family, though; he felt as if he were going to crawl out of his skin.  Ever since he\rquote d been a boy in England he\rquote 
d had a repetitive fantasy that he was actually a reptile and could shed his own skin.  He\rquote d had the dream long before he\rquote d read any Kafka; he still had the disturbing dream.
\par He rolled three dice in his hand as he sipped his wine, played the game at the dinner table.  If the number seventeen came up, he would murder them all tonight.
\par He swore he would do it.  First the twins, then Robert, and finally Lucy.
\par She kept prattling on and on about her day.  He smiled blithely as she told him about her shopping trip to Bloomingdale\rquote s and Bath & Body Works and Bruno Cipriani at the mall.  He considered the supreme irony of t
aking truckloads of antidepressants, and being more depressed.  Jesus, he was cycling down again.  How low could he go?
\par \lquote Come, seventeen.\rquote   he finally said aloud.
\par \lquote What, darling?\rquote   Lucy suddenly asked.  \lquote Did you just say something?\rquote 
\par \lquote He\rquote s already playing tonight\rquote s game.\rquote   said Robert, and snickered.  \lquote Right, Daddy?  It\rquote s your fantasy game.  Am I right?\rquote 
\par \lquote Right, son.\rquote   Shafer replied, thinking, Christ, I am mad!
\par He let the dice gently fall on the dining table, though.  He would kill them - if their number came up.  The dice rolled over and over, finally banking off the greasy pizza box.
\par \lquote Daddy and his games.\rquote   Lucy said, and laughed.  Erica and Tricia laughed.  Robert laughed.
\par Six, five, one, he counted.  Damn, damn.
\par \lquote Are the two of us going to play tonight?\rquote   Robert asked.
\par Shafer forced a smile.  \lquote Not tonight, Rob Boy.  I\rquote d like to, but I can\rquote t.  I have to go out again.\rquote 
\par 
