\par This was getting very interesting.  Patsy Hampton watched Shafer leave the large and expensive house in Kalorama around eight thirty.  He was off on another of his nightly jaunts.  The guy was a regular vampire.
\par She knew that Cross and his friends called the killer the Weasel, and it certainly fit Shafer.  There was something uncomfortable about him, something bent.
\par She followed the black Jag, but he didn\rquote t head toward Southeast, which disappointed her.  He drove to a trendy supermarket, Sutton on the Run, which was just off Dupont Circle.  Hampton knew the pricey store and called it Why Pay Less.
\par He parked the sports car illegally, then jogged inside.  Diplomatic immunity.  That pissed her the hell off.  What a weasel he was, real Euro-trash.
\par While he was in the market, Hampton made a command decision.  She was pretty sure she was going to talk to Alex Cross.  She had thoug
ht a lot about it, the pros and cons.  Now she figured that she might be endangering lives in Southeast by not sharing at least some of what she knew.  If someone died, she wouldn\rquote 
t be able to bear it.  Besides, Cross would have gotten the information if she hadn\rquote t interceded with Chuck Hufstedler.
\par Shafer shuffled back out of Sutton on the Run and glanced around crowded Dupont Circle.  He had a small bag of overpriced groceries clutched in one arm.  Groceries for whom, though?  He didn\rquote t look in the directi
on of her Jeep, which was just peeking around the corner.
\par She followed the black Jag at a safe distance in the light traffic.  He got on Connecticut Avenue.  She didn\rquote t think he\rquote d spotted her, though he was an MI6 man, so she needed to be careful.
\par Shafer wasn\rquote t far from Embassy Row.  He wouldn\rquote t be going back to work now, would he?  Why the groceries if he was headed to the embassy?
\par The Jaguar eventually turned into the underground garage of a prewar building in Woodley Park.  THE FARRAGUT was engraved on a brass sign in front.
\par Patsy Hampton waited a few minutes, then she pulled into the garage behind the attendant in a small kiosk and identified herself.
\par "The Jag that came in before me, ever see it here before?\rquote  she asked.
\par The man nodded.  He was around her age and she could tell he wanted to impress her if he could.  \lquote Sure.  I don\rquote t know him to talk to, though.  Comes here to visit a lady on ten.  Dr. Elizabeth Cassady.  She\rquote s a shrink.  I assume he
\rquote s a patient.  He\rquote s got a funny look in his eyes.\rquote   the attendant said, \lquote but so do most people.\rquote 
\par \lquote How about me?\rquote   Hampton asked.
\par \lquote Nah.  Well, maybe a little.\rquote   the attendant said, and grinned.
\par Shafer stayed upstairs with Dr. Cassady for nearly two hours.  Then he came down and went straight back to the house in Kalorama.
\par Patsy Hampton followed him, then watched the house for another half-hour.  She thought that Shafer was probably in for the night.  She drove to a nearby diner but didn\rquote t go inside right away.  She picked up her mobile phone before she had too many 
second thoughts.  She knew Cross\rquote s street, and got the phone number through information.  Was it too late to call?  Screw it, she was going through with this.
\par She was surprised when the phone was picked up on the first ring.  She heard a pleasant male voice.  Nice.  Strong.
\par \lquote Hello.  Alex Cross.\rquote 
\par She almost hung up on him.  Interesting that he\rquote d intimidated her for a moment.  \lquote This is Detective Patsy Hampton.  I\rquote ve been doing some work on the Jane Does.  I\rquote ve been following a man who is a suspect.  I think w
e should talk.\rquote 
\par \lquote Where are you, Patsy?\rquote   Cross said, without hesitation.  \lquote I\rquote ll come to you.  Just tell me where.\rquote 
\par \lquote I\rquote m at the City Limits diner on Connecticut Avenue.\rquote 
\par \lquote I\rquote m on my way,\rquote  said Cross.
