\par I wasn\rquote t totally surprised that Pittman had assigned someone to the Jane Does.  Especially after Zach Taylor\rquote s article in the Washington Post.  I was interested in any leads Detective Hampton might have turned up.
\par I had seen Patsy Hampton around and she obviously knew who I was.  She was supposed to be on a fast track; she was a smart and effective senior homicide detective, though from what I\rquote d heard, she was also a lone wolf.  She didn\rquote 
t have any friends in the department, as far as I knew.
\par She was much prettier than I remembered.  She was in very trim, athletic shape, probably early thirties, short blonde hair, piercing blue eyes that cut through the diner haze.
\par She\rquote d put on bright-red lipstick for our meeting, or maybe she wore it all the time.  I wondered what was on her mind and what her motives were.  I didn\rquote t think I could trust her.
\par \lquote You or me first?\rquote   Detective Hampton asked, after we\rquote d ordered coffee.  We were seated at a table in the City Limits diner, near a window looking out on Connecticut Avenue.
\par \lquote I\rquote m afraid I don\rquote t know what this is about.\rquote   I told her.
\par She sipped her coffee and gave me a look over the cup\rquote s rim.  She was a strong-willed, confident person.  Her eyes told me that much.
\par \lquote You really didn\rquote t know someone else was working on the Jane Does?\rquote 
\par I shook my head.  \lquote Pittman said that the cases were closed.  I took him at his word.  He suspended some good detectives for working the cases after hours.\rquote 
\par \lquote There\rquote s a lot of seriously nasty crap going on in the department.  So what\rquote s new though,\rquote  she said as she set down her cup.  She gave a deep sigh.  \lquote I thought I could deal with it by myself.  Now I\rquote m not so sure.
\rquote 
\par \lquote Pittman assigned you to the Jane Does?  Personally?\rquote 
\par She nodded, then her blue eyes narrowed.  \lquote He assigned me to the Glover and Cardinal murders, and any others I wanted to look into.  Gave me free rein.\rquote 
\par \lquote And you say you have something?\rquote 
\par \lquote Maybe.  I\rquote ve got a possible suspect.  He\rquote s involved in a role-playing game that features victims being murdered, mostly in Southeast.  It\rquote s all after-the-fact stuff, so he could hav
e read the news stories and then fantasized about them.  He works at the British Embassy.\rquote 
\par This was a new piece of information, and it surprised me.  \lquote How far have you gone with this?\rquote 
\par \lquote Not to Pittman, if that\rquote s what you mean.  I\rquote ve done a little discreet checking on the suspect.  Trouble is, he seems to be a solid citizen.  Very good at his job - supposedly.  At least that\rquote 
s the official word from the embassy.  Nice family in Kalorama.  I\rquote ve been watching Shafer a little, hoping I\rquote d get lucky.  His first name is Geoffrey.\rquote 
\par I knew she was supposed to be a little bit of a loose cannon, and that she didn\rquote t suffer fools gladly.  \lquote You\rquote re out here alone tonight?\rquote   I asked her.
\par Hampton shrugged.  \lquote That\rquote s how I usually operate.  Partners slow me down.  Chief Pittman knows how I like to work.  He gave me the green light.  All green, all day long.\rquote 
\par I knew that she was waiting for me to give her something - if I had anything.  I decided to play along.  \lquote We found a cab that the killer apparently used in Southeast.  He kept it in a garage in Eckington.\rquote 
\par \lquote Anybody see the suspect in the neighborhood?\rquote   She asked the right first question.
\par \lquote The landlady saw him.  I\rquote d like to show her pictures of your guy.  Or you want to do it yourself?\rquote 
\par Her face was impassive.  \lquote I\rquote ll do it.  First thing in the morning.  Anything revealing in the apartment?\rquote 
\par I decided to be straight with her.  She\rquote d initiated the meeting, after all.  \lquote Photographs of me and my family covered a wall in a closet.  They were taken of us in Bermuda.  While we were on vacation.  He was there watching us all the time.
\rquote 
\par Hampton nodded gently.  \lquote I heard your fianc\'e9e disappeared in Bermuda.  Word gets around.\rquote 
\par \lquote There were photographs of Christine too.\rquote   I said.
\par Her blue eyes softened.  I got a quick look behind her tough facade.  I\rquote m really sorry about your loss.\rquote 
\par \lquote I haven\rquote t given up yet.\rquote   I told her.  \lquote Listen, I don\rquote t want any credit for solving these cases, just let me help.  He called me at home last night.  Somebody did.  Told me to back off.  I assume that he meant 
this investigation, but I\rquote m not supposed to be on it.  If Pittman hears about us\emdash \rquote 
\par Detective Hampton interrupted me.  \lquote Let me think about everything you\rquote ve said.  You know that Pittman will totally crucify me if he finds out.  You have no idea.  Trouble is, I don\rquote t trust him.\rquote   Hampton\rquote 
s gaze was intense and direct.  \lquote Don\rquote t mention any of this to your buddies, or Sampson.  You never know.  Just let me sleep on it.  I\rquote ll try to do the right thing.  I\rquote m not such a hardass really.  Just a little weird, you know.
\rquote 
\par \lquote Aren\rquote t we all.\rquote   I said, and smiled.  Hampton was a tough detective, but I felt okay about her.  I took something out of my pocket.  A beeper.
\par \lquote Keep this.  If you get in trouble or get another lead, you can beep me anytime.  If you find something out, please let me know.  I\rquote ll do the same.  If Shafer\rquote 
s the one, I want to talk to him before we bring him in.  This is personal for me.  You can\rquote t imagine how personal.\rquote 
\par Hampton continued to make eye contact, studying me.  She reminded me of someone I\rquote d known a while back, another complicated woman cop named Jezzie Flanagan.  \lquote I\rquote ll think about it.  I\rquote ll let you know.\rquote 
\par \lquote All right.  Thanks for calling me in on this.\rquote 
\par She stood.  \lquote You\rquote re not in on it yet.  Like I said, I\rquote ll let you know.\rquote   Then she touched my hand.  \lquote I really am sorry about your friend.\rquote 
\par 
\par 
