\par We both knew I was in, though.  We\rquote d made some kind of a deal in the City Limits diner.  I just hoped I wasn\rquote t being set up by Hampton and Pittman or God knows who else.
\par During the next two days we talked four times.  I still wasn\rquote t sure that I could trust her, but I didn\rquote t have a choice.  I had to keep moving forward.  She had already visited the landlady who\rquote 
d rented out the apartment and garage in Eckington.  The landlady hadn\rquote t recognized the pictures of Shafer.  Possibly he\rquote d worn some kind of disguise when he met with her.
\par If Patsy Hampton was setting me up, she was one of the best liars I\rquote d met, and I\rquote ve known some good ones.  During one of the calls, she confessed that Chuck Hufstedler had been her source, and that she\rquote 
d gotten him to keep the information from me.  I shrugged it off.  I didn\rquote t have the time or energy to be angry at either of them.
\par In the meantime, I spent a lot of time at home.  I didn\rquote t believe the killer would come after my family, not when he already had Christine, but I couldn\rquote t tell that for sure.  When I wasn\rquote 
t there, I made sure Sampson or somebody else was checking on the house.
\par On the third night after I met her, Patsy Hampton and I had a breakthrough of sorts.  She actually invited me to join her on the stakeout at Shafer\rquote s town house in Kalorama Heights.
\par He had arrived home from work before six and remained there until past nine.  He had a nice-looking ex-pat family, three children, a wife, a nanny.  He lived very well.  Nothing about his life or surroundings suggested he might be a killer.
\par \lquote He seems to go out every night around this time,\rquote  Hampton told me as we watched him walk to a shiny black Jag parked in a graveled driveway on the side of the house.
\par \lquote Creature of habit,\rquote  I said.  A weasel.
\par \lquote Creature anyway,\rquote  she said.  We both smiled.  The ice was breaking up a little between us.  She admitted that she had checked me out thoroughly.  She\rquote d decided that Chief Pittman was the bad guy in all of this, not me.
\par The Jaguar pulled out of the drive and we followed Shafer to a night spot in Georgetown.  He didn\rquote t seem to be aware of us.  The problem was that we had to catch him doing something; we had no concrete evidence that he was our killer.
\par Shafer sat by himself at the bar and we watched him from the street.  Did he perch by the window on purpose?  I wondered.  Did he know we were watching?  Was he playing with us?
\par I had a bad feeling that he was.  This was all some kind of bizarre game to him.  He left the bar around a quarter to twelve and returned home just past midnight.
\par \lquote Bastard.\rquote   Patsy grimaced, and shook her head.  Her blonde hair was soft and had a nice bounce to it.  She definitely reminded me of Jezzie Flanagan, a Secret Service agent I\rquote d worked with on t
he kidnapping of two children in Georgetown.
\par \lquote He\rquote s in for the night?\rquote   I asked.  \lquote What was that all about?  He leaves the house to watch the Orioles baseball game at a bar in Georgetown?\rquote 
\par \lquote That\rquote s how it\rquote s been the last few nights.  I think he knows we\rquote re out here.\rquote 
\par \lquote He\rquote s an intelligence officer.  He knows surveillance.  We also know he likes to play fantasy games.  At any rate, he\rquote s home for the night, so I\rquote m going home too, Patsy.  I don\rquote t like leaving my family alone too long.
\rquote 
\par \lquote Goodnight, Alex.  Thanks for the help.  We\rquote ll get him.  And maybe we\rquote ll find your friend soon.\rquote 
\par \lquote I hope so.\rquote 
\par On the drive home, I thought a little about Detective Patsy Hampton.  She struck me as a lonely person, and I wondered why.  She was thoughtful and interesting once you got 
past her tough facade.  I wondered if anyone could really get through the facade though.
\par There was a light on in our kitchen when I rolled into the driveway.  I strolled around to the back door and saw Damon and Nana, in their bathrobes at the stove.  Everything seemed all right.
\par \lquote Am I breaking up a pajama party?\rquote   I asked as I eased in through the back door.
\par \lquote Damon has an upset stomach.  I heard him in the kitchen so I came out to get in his way.\rquote 
\par \lquote I\rquote m all right.  I just couldn\rquote t sleep.  I saw you were still out,\rquote  he said.  \lquote It\rquote s after midnight.\rquote 
\par He looked worried, and also a little sad.  Damon had really liked Christine and he told me a couple of times that he was looking forward to having a mom again.  He\rquote d already begun to think of her that way.  He and 
Jannie missed Christine a whole lot.  Twice, they\rquote d had important women taken away from them.
\par \lquote I was working a little late.  That\rquote s all.  It\rquote s a very complicated case, Damon, but I think I\rquote m making progress,\rquote  I said.  I went to the cabinet and took out two tea bags.
\par \lquote I\rquote ll make you tea,\rquote  Nana offered.
