\par Elizabeth \lquote Boo\rquote  Cassady was in her late thirties, slender and very attractive, with lustrous brown hair that she had worn long since she was a young girl.  She was a regular shopper at Neiman Marcus, Saks, Nordstrom, Bloomingdale\rquote 
s, and various chic specialty shops around Washington.  It showed.
\par She had gotten the nickname \lquote Boo\rquote  as an infant because she always laughed and laughed whenever she heard the sound of somebody playing \lquote peek-a-boo\rquote  with her.  She soon learned to make it herself, muttering \lquote 
boo, boo, boo, boo\rquote .  In school, right through college, she kept the name, friends said, because she could be a little scary at times.
\par For her important day in court she\rquote d chosen a single-breasted pantsuit, beautifully cut, very soft and flowy.  Her outfit was an eye-pleasing mix of coffee and cashmere cream.  She looked like a professional person, and a successful one.
\par Jules Halpern asked her to state her name and occupation for the record.  He was amiable but businesslike, a little cooler than he had been with other witnesses.
\par \lquote Dr. Elizabeth Cassady.  I\rquote m a psychotherapist,\rquote  she replied evenly.
\par \lquote Dr. Cassady, how do you know Colonel Shafer?\rquote 
\par \lquote He\rquote s a patient of mine and has been for over a year.  He sees me at my office at 1208 Woodley Avenue once or twice a week.  We increased the sessions recently since Mr. Shafer\rquote s attempted suicide.\rquote 
\par Halpern nodded.  \lquote What time are the sessions?\rquote 
\par \lquote Usually early evenings.  They can vary according to Mr. Shafer\rquote s work schedule.\rquote 
\par \lquote Dr. Cassady, I direct your attention to the evening of the murder of Detective Hampton.  Did Geoffrey Shafer have a therapy session with you that night?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, he did.  At nine p.m., nine until ten.  I think he may have arrived a little earlier that night.  But the session was scheduled for nine.\rquote 
\par \lquote Could he have arrived as early as eight thirty?\rquote 
\par \lquote No.  That isn\rquote t possible.  We were talking to each othe
r on cell phones from the time he left his house in Kalorama until he arrived at my building.  He was feeling a great deal of guilt about his latest dark mood coming too close to his daughters\rquote  birthday party.\rquote 
\par \lquote I see.  Was there any break in your conversation with Colonel Shafer?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes.  But it was a very short one.\rquote 
\par Halpern kept the pace brisk.  \lquote How much time passed between the time the two of you stopped talking on the cell phone and his arrival at your office?\rquote 
\par \lquote Two or three minutes, five at the most.  While he parked and came upstairs.  No more than that.\rquote 
\par \lquote When he arrived at your office, did Geoffrey Shafer seem unsettled in any way?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, not at all.  He appeared relatively cheerful, actually.  He had just hosted a successful birthday party for the twins.  He felt it had gone very well and he dotes on his children.\rquote 
\par \lquote Was he out of breath, tense, or perspiring?\rquote   Halpern asked.
\par \lquote No.  As I said, he was calm and looked quite fine.  I remember it very clearly.  And after the intrusion by the police, I made careful notes to keep everything accurate and fresh,\rquote  she said, then glanced at the prosecutor\rquote s table.

\par \lquote So, you made notes for the sake of accuracy?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, I did.\rquote 
\par \lquote Dr. Cassady, did you notice any blood anywhere on Colonel Sharer\rquote s clothing?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, I did not.\rquote 
\par \lquote I see.  You saw no blood on Shafer.  And when Detective Cross arrived, did you see any blood on him?\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, I saw dark stains or streaks\rquote  of blood on his shirt and suit coat.  Also on his hands.\rquote 
\par Jules Halpern paused to let everything sink in with the jury.  Then he asked a final question.  \lquote Did Colonel Shafer look as if he had just murdered someone?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, certainly not.\rquote 
\par \lquote I have nothing further,\rquote  said the defense attorney.
\par Daniel Weston did the cross-exam for the prosecution.  He was twenty-nine years old, bright, quick-witted, a rising star, and known to be a ruthless hatchet man in the prosecutor\rquote s office.
\par Dan Weston was also good-looking, blond, and rugged.  He got physically close to Boo Cassady.  They made a fetching couple, which was the visual idea he wanted to communicate.
\par \lquote Ms. Cassady, you weren\rquote t Mr. Shafer\rquote s psychiatrist, were you?\rquote 
\par She frowned slightly, but then managed a weak smile.  \lquote No, a psychiatrist has to be a medical doctor.  You know that, I\rquote m sure.\rquote 
\par \lquote And you are not a medical doctor?\rquote 
\par She shook her head.  \lquote I am not.  I have a doctorate in sociology.  You know that, too.\rquote 
\par \lquote Are you a psychologist?\rquote   Weston asked.
\par \lquote A psychologist usually has a graduate degree in psychology, sometimes a Ph.D.\rquote 
\par \lquote Do you have a graduate degree in psychology?\rquote 
\par \lquote No.  I\rquote m a psychotherapist.\rquote 
\par \lquote I see.  Where was your training to be a psychotherapist?\rquote 
\par \lquote American University.  I graduated with a Ph.D. in social work.\rquote 
\par Daniel Weston kept coming at Cassady.  There was hardly a beat between question and answer.  \lquote This "psycho-therapy office" of yours at the Farragut.  What sort of furnishings does it have?\rquote 
\par \lquote A couch, desk, lamp.  It\rquote s basically very spare.  Lots of plants, though.  My patients find the atmosphere functional but also relaxing.\rquote 
\par \lquote No box of tissues by the couch?  I thought that was a must.\rquote   Weston said with a thin smile.
\par The witness was clearly annoyed now, and maybe even shaken.  \lquote I take my work very seriously, Mr. Weston.  So do my patients.\rquote 
\par \lquote Was Geoffrey Shafer referred to you by someone?\rquote 
\par \lquote Actually, we met in the National Gallery...  at the Picasso Erotic Drawing Exhibit.  That\rquote s been covered in depth by the press.\rquote 
\par Weston nodded, and a thin smile crossed his lips.  \lquote Ah, I see.  Are your sessions with Geoffrey Shafer erotic?  Do you ever discuss sex?\rquote 
\par Jules Halpern rose quickly; a regular Jules-in-the-box.  \lquote Objection!  Doctor/patient privilege.  It\rquote s confidential.\rquote 
\par The young prosecutor shrugged, flipped back his blond curls with his hand.  \lquote I\rquote ll withdraw the question.  No problem.  Are you a sexual surrogate?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, I am not.  As I stated earlier, I am a psychotherapist.\rquote 
\par \lquote On the evening of the murder of Detective Hampton, did you and Geoffrey Shafer discuss\emdash \rquote 
\par Jules Halpern quickly rose again.  \lquote Objection.  If the prosecution is inquiring into the patient\rquote s privileged disclosures\emdash \rquote 
\par Weston raised both arms in frustration.  He smiled at the jury, hoping they felt the same way.  \lquote All right, all right.  Let me see.  I\rquote ll take this out of the so-called doctor/patient realm and ask you, quite simply, if you,
 Ms. Cassady, a woman, have had sexual relations with Geoffrey Shafer, a man?\rquote 
\par Elizabeth \lquote Boo\rquote  Cassady hung her head and stared down at her lap.
\par Daniel Weston smiled, even as Jules Halpern objected to the question and was upheld by Judge Fescoe.  Weston felt that he had made his point.
