\par I took a back way out of the courthouse.  I usually did, but on this day it was essential.  I had to avoid the crowds and the press, and I needed to have a private moment to recover from my time on the witness stand.
\par I\rquote d just had my ass pretty well kicked by an expert asskicker.  Tomorrow, Cathy Fitzgibbon would try to undo some of the damage in cross-exam.
\par I was in no hurry as I walked down a back stairway that was used by maintenance and cleaning people in the building, and was also a fire escape.
\par It was becoming clear to me that there was a chance that Geoffrey Shafer would be acquitted.  His lawyers were the best.  We\rquote d lost important evidence at the suppression hearing.
\par And, I had made a mistake at the homicide scene in my rush to help Patsy Hampton without putting on gloves.
\par It was an honest mistake, but it probably created doubt in the minds of the jurors.  I\rquote d had more blood on me than Shafer.  That was true.  Shafer might actually get away with murder, and I couldn\rquote 
t stand the thought.  I felt like yelling as I descended the twisting flight of stairs.
\par And that\rquote s what I did, finally.  I yelled at the top of my voice and it felt so damn good to get it out.  Relief flowed through my body, however temporary it might be.
\par At the bottom of the concrete stairs was the basement of the courthouse.  I headed down a long darkened hallway toward the rear lot where the Porsche was parked.  I was still lost i
n my thoughts, but calmer after hollering my fool head off in the stairwell.
\par There was a sharp bend in the hallway near the exit to the parking lot.  I came around the turn and saw him.  I couldn\rquote t believe it.  The Weasel was right there.
\par He was first to speak.  \lquote What a surprise, Dr. Cross.  Sneaking away from the madding, or is it maddening crowd?  Tail between your legs today?  Don\rquote 
t fret, you did all right upstairs.  Was that you yelling in the halls?  Primal screams are the best, aren\rquote t they?\rquote 
\par \lquote What the hell do you want, Shafer?\rquote   I asked him.  \lquote We\rquote re not supposed to meet or talk like this.\rquote 
\par He shrugged his broad shoulders, wiped his blond hair away from his eyes.  \lquote You think I care about rules?  I don\rquote t give a shit about rules.  What do I want?  My good
 name restored.  I want my family not to have to go through any more of this.  I want it all.\rquote 
\par \lquote Then you shouldn\rquote t have killed all those people.  Especially Patsy Hampton.\rquote 
\par Shafer finally smiled.  \lquote You\rquote re very sure of yourself, aren\rquote t you?  You don\rquote t back down.  I admire that, to a degree.  I played the game of being a hero once myself.  In the army.  It\rquote s interesting for a while.\rquote 

\par \lquote But it\rquote s much more interesting to be a raving lunatic murderer,\rquote  I said.
\par \lquote See?  You just don\rquote t back down from your pig-headed opinions.  I love it.  You\rquote re wonderful.\rquote 
\par \lquote It\rquote s not opinion, Shafer.  You know it, and so do I.\rquote 
\par \lquote Then prove it, Cross.  Win your pitiful sodding case, will you?  Beat me fair and square in a court of law.  I even gave you home advantage.\rquote 
\par I started to walk toward him; I couldn\rquote t help myself.  He stood his ground.
\par \lquote This is all an insane game to you.  I\rquote ve met assholes like you before, Shafer.  I\rquote ve beaten better.  I\rquote ll beat you.\rquote 
\par He laughed in my face.  \lquote I sincerely doubt it.\rquote 
\par I walked right past him in the narrow tunnel.
\par He pushed me - hard, from behind.  He was a big man, but even stronger than he looked.
\par I stumbled, almost went over onto the stone floor.  I wasn\rquote t expecting the outburst of anger from him.  He held it in so well in court, but it was close to the surface.  The madness that was Geoffrey Shafer.  The violence.
\par \lquote Then go ahead, beat me.  See if you can,\rquote  he yelled at the top of his voice.  \lquote Beat me right here, right now.  I don\rquote t think you can, Cross.  I know you can\rquote t.\rquote 
\par Shafer took a quick step toward me.  He was agile and athletic, not just strong.  We were almost the same size, six foot two or three, two hundred pounds.  I remembered that he\rquote d been an army officer, then MI6.  He still looked in excellent shape.

\par Shafer pushed me again with both hands.  He made a loud grunting noise.  \lquote If you\rquote ve beaten better, then I should be a pushover.  Isn\rquote t that so?  I\rquote m just a pushover.\rquote 
\par I almost threw a punch; I wanted to.  I ached to take him down, to wipe the smug, superior look off his face.
\par Instead, I grabbed him hard.  I slammed Shafer up against the stone tunnel wall and held him there.
\par \lquote Not now.  Not here,\rquote  I said, in a hoarse, raw whisper.  I\rquote m not going to hit you, Shafer.  What?  Have you run to the newspapers and TV.  But I am going to bring you down.  Soon.\rquote 
\par He came out with a crazy laugh.  \lquote You are fucking hilarious, do you know that?  You\rquote re a scream.  I love it.\rquote 
\par I walked away from Shafer in the dark tunnel.  It was the hardest thing I\rquote ve ever had to do.  I wanted to beat the answers out of him, get a confession.  I wanted to know about Christine.  I had so many questions, but I knew he wouldn\rquote 
t answer them.  He was here to bait me, to play.
\par \lquote You\rquote re losing ...  everything,\rquote  he said to my back.
\par I think I could have killed Geoffrey Shafer on the spot.
\par I almost turned, but I didn\rquote 
t.  I opened the creaking door and went outside instead.  Sunlight streamed into my eyes, half-blinding me for a dizzying moment.  Shading my face with an arm, I climbed stone stairs to the parking area, where I got another unwanted surprise.
\par A dozen grim-faced members of the press, including some important reporters, were gathered in the back parking lot.  Someone had alerted them; someone had tipped them off that I was coming out this way.
\par I looked back at the gray metal door, but Geoffrey Shafer didn\rquote t come out behind me.  He had retreated and disappeared back into the basement.
\par \lquote Detective Cross.\rquote  I heard a reporter call my name.  \lquote You\rquote re losing this case.  You know that, don\rquote t you?\rquote 
\par Yes, I knew.  I was losing everything.  I just didn\rquote t know what I could do to stop it.
\par 
