\par The following day was taken up with my cross-examination by Catherine Fitzgibbon.  Catherine did a good job of redressing some of the harm done by Jules Halpern, but not all of it.  H
alpern consistently broke up her rhythm with his objections.  Like so many recent high-profile trials, this one was maddening.  It should have been easy to convict and put away Geoffrey Shafer, but that wasn\rquote t the case.
\par Two days later, we got our best chance to win, and Shafer himself gave it to us, almost as if he was daring us.  Now we realized that he was even crazier than we\rquote d thought.  The game was his life; nothing else seemed to matter.
\par Shafer agreed to take the stand.  I think that I was the only one in the courtroom who wasn\rquote t completely surprised that he was testifying, that he was playing the game right in front of us.
\par Catherine Fitzgibbon was almost certain that Jules Halpern had lectured, pleaded and advised him against it; but there Shafer was 
anyway, striding toward the witness stand, looking as if he had been called up there to be ceremoniously knighted by the Queen.
\par He couldn\rquote t resist the stage, could he?  He looked every bit as confident and in control as he had the night I arrested him for Patsy Hampton\rquote 
s murder.  He was dressed in a navy-blue double-breasted suit, white shirt, and gold tie.  Not a single blond hair was out of place, nor was there any hint of the anger boiling just under the surface of his meticulously groomed exterior.
\par Jules Halpern addressed him in conversational tones, but I was certain that he was uneasy about this unnecessary gamble.
\par \lquote Colonel Shafer, first I want to thank you for coming to the witness stand.  This is completely voluntary on your part.  From the beginning, you\rquote ve stated that you wanted to come here to clear your name.\rquote 
\par Shafer smiled politely, and then cut off his lawyer with a raised hand.  The lawyers on both sides of the bar exchanged looks.  What was happening?  What was he going to do?
\par I leaned way forward in my seat.  It struck me that Jules Halpern might actually know that his client was guilty.  If he did, he wouldn\rquote t have been able to cross-examine him.  Legally, he couldn\rquote 
t ask questions that disguised the real facts as he knew them.
\par This was the o
nly way that Shafer could have his moment in the sun: a soliloquy.  Once called to the stand, Shafer could give a speech.  It was unusual, but absolutely legal - and, if Halpern knew his client was guilty, it was the only way that Shafer could take the st
and and not be incriminated by his own attorney.
\par Shafer had the floor.  \lquote If you will please excuse me, Mr. Halpern, I believe I can talk to these good people myself.  I really can manage.  You see, I don\rquote t need a lot of expert help telling the simple truth.\rquote 
\par Jules Halpern stepped back, nodded sagely, and tried to keep his poise.  What else could he do under the circumstances?  If he hadn\rquote t known his client was an egomaniac or insane, he surely knew it now.
\par Shafer looked toward the jury.  \lquote It has been stated here in court that I am with British Intelligence, that I was MI6, a spy.  I\rquote m afraid that I am actually a rather unglamorous agent, Double-O-Nothing if you will.\rquote 
\par The light, well-aimed jab at himself drew laughter in the courtroom.
\par \lquote I am a simple bureaucr
at, like so many others who toil away their days and nights in Washington.  I follow well-established procedures at the embassy.  I get approvals for virtually everything I do.  My home life is simple and orderly as well.  My wife and I have been married 
nearly sixteen years.  We love each other dearly.  We\rquote re devoted to our three children.\rquote 
\par \lquote So I want to apologize to my wife and children.  I am so frightfully sorry for this hellish ordeal they\rquote ve had to go through.  To my son, Rob, and the twins, Tricia and Erica, I\rquote 
m so sorry.  If I had any idea what a circus this would become, I would have insisted on diplomatic immunity, rather than clear my name, our name, their name.\rquote 
\par \lquote While I\rquote m making heartfelt apologies, I\rquote ll make one to all of you for being a bit of a bore right now.  It\rquote s just that - when you\rquote 
re accused of murder, something so heinous, so unthinkable, you want desperately to get it off your chest.  You want to tell the truth more than anything else in the world.  So that\rquote s what I\rquote m doing today.\rquote 
\par \lquote You\rquote ve heard the evidence - and there simply isn\rquote t any.  You\rquote ve heard character witnesses.  And now you\rquote 
ve heard from me.  I did not kill Detective Patsy Hampton.  I think you all know that, but I wanted to say it to you myself.  Thank you for listening,\rquote  he said, and bowed slightly in his seat.
\par Shafer was brief, but he was poised and articulate, and, unfortunately, very believable.  He always held eye contact with the jury members.  His words weren\rquote t nearly as important as the way he delivered them.
\par Catherine Fitzgibbon came forward to do the cross-examination, and she was careful with Shafer at first.  She knew that he had the jury on his side for the moment.
\par She waited until near the end of her cross-exam to go after Shafer where he might be most vulnerable.
\par \lquote That was very nice, Mr. Shafer.  Now as you sit before this jury you claim that your relationship with Dr. Cassady was strictly professional, that you did not have a sexual relationship with her?  Remember you are under oath.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, absolutely.  She was, and hopefully will continue to be, my therapist.\rquote 
\par \lquote Notwithstanding the fact that she admits to having a sexual relationship with you?\rquote 
\par Shafer held his hand toward Jules Halpern, signaling for him not to object.  \lquote I believe that the court record will show that she did not admit to such.\rquote 
\par Fitzgibbon frowned.  \lquote I don\rquote t follow?  Why do you think she didn\rquote t answer counsel?\rquote 
\par Shafer shot back.  \lquote That\rquote s obvious.  Because she didn\rquote t care to dignify such a question.\rquote 
\par \lquote And when she hung her head, sir, and looked down at her lap?  She was nodding assent?\rquote 
\par Shafer now looked at the jury, and shook his head in amazement.  \lquote You misread her completely.  You missed the point again, Counselor.  Allow me to illustrate, if I may.  As Charles the First said before being beheade
d, "Give me my cloak lest they think I tremble from fear."  Dr. Elizabeth Cassady was deeply embarrassed by your associate\rquote s crude suggestion, so was my family, and so am I.\rquote 
\par Geoffrey Shafer looked at the prosecutor with steely eyes.  He then acknowledged the jury again.  \lquote And so am I.\rquote 
\par 
