\par The trial was almost over, and now came the really hard part: waiting for a verdict.  That Tuesday, the jurors retired to the jury room to commence their deliberations in the murder trial of Geoffrey S
hafer.  For the first time, I allowed myself to actually think the unthinkable: that Shafer might be set free.
\par Sampson and I sat in the rear row of the courtroom and watched the twelve members depart: eight men and four women.  John had come to court several times, calling it the \lquote best and sleaziest show this side of the Oval Office\rquote 
, but I knew he was there to give me support.
\par \lquote The sonofabitch is guilty, he\rquote s mad as little Davey Berkowitz,\rquote  Sampson said as he watched Shafer.  \lquote But he has a lot of good acto
rs on his side: doting wife, doting mistress, well-paid lawyers, Silly Billy.  He could get away with it.\rquote 
\par \lquote It happens,\rquote  I agreed.  \lquote Juries are hard to read.  And getting harder.\rquote 
\par I watched as Shafer courteously shook hands with the members of his defense team.  Both Jules and Jane Halpern had forced smiles on their faces.  They knew, didn\rquote t they?  Their client was the Weasel, a mass murderer.
