\par He felt so damn good.  So fine.  God, how he had missed this.  The mainline of adrenaline, the incomparable thrill.  He knew it was likely that the Jamaica Inn was being watched by the police, so he parked the Mustang at the nearby Plantation Inn.
\par He walked at a quickening pace through the crowded Bougainvillea Terrace.  Drinks were being served while the wretched song \lquote Yellowbird\rquote 
 played loudly.  He had a nasty fantasy about shooting up the terrace, killing several dickhead tourists, so he got away from the crowded area immediately, for everybody\rquote s sake, but mostly his own.
\par He strolled the beach and it calmed him.  It wa
s quiet, restful, with strains of calypso music gently weaving through the night air.  The stretch between the two hotels was eye-catching, plenty of spotlights, sand the color of champagne, thatched umbrellas at even intervals.  A very nice playing field
.
\par He knew where Oliver Highsmith was staying, the famous White Suite, where Winston Churchill and David Niven and lan Fleming had all slept once upon a time.  Highsmith loved his creature comforts almost as much as he loved the game itself.  Shafer despised
 the other Horsemen, partly because he wasn\rquote t in their social class.  Lucy\rquote s father had got him into MI6; the other players had been from the right backgrounds.  Shafer\rquote s didn\rquote 
t quite match up.  But there was another, more powerful reason for his hatred: they had dared to use him, to feel superior and throw it in his face.
\par He entered through a white picket-fence gate at the property line of the Jamaica Inn.  He broke into a soft jog.  He wanted to run, to sweat.  He was feeling manic again.  Playing the game had made him too excited.
\par Shafer held his head for a moment.  He wanted to laugh and scream at the top of his lungs.  He leaned against a wooden post leading up from the beach, and tried to catch his breath.  He realized he was crashing and it couldn\rquote t h
ave happened at a worse time.
\par \lquote Everything all right, sir?\rquote  a hotel waiter stopped and asked him.
\par \lquote Oh, couldn\rquote t be better.\rquote   Shafer said, waving the man away.  \lquote I\rquote m in heaven, can\rquote t you tell?\rquote 
\par He started walking toward the White Suite again.  He realized that he was feeling the way he had the morning he\rquote 
d nearly crashed his car in Washington.  He was in serious trouble again.  He could lose the game right now, lose everything.  That required a change of strategy, didn\rquote t it?  He had to be more daring, even mo
re aggressive.  He had to act, not think too much.  The odds against him were still two to one.
\par At the far end of the courtyard, he spotted a man and a woman in evening clothes.  They were loitering near a white stucco portico strewn with flowers.  He decided they were Jones\rquote 
s people.  They had staked out the hotel, after all.  They were here for him and he was honored.
\par The male glanced his way, and Shafer abruptly lowered his head.  There was nothing they could do to stop or detain him.  He\rquote d committed no crime they could prove.  He wasn\rquote t wanted by the police.  No, he was a free man.
\par So Shafer walked toward them at a leisurely pace, as if he hadn\rquote t seen them.  He whistled \lquote Yellowbird\rquote .
\par He looked up when he was a few yards away from the pair.  \lquote I\rquote m the one you\rquote re waiting for.  I\rquote m Geoffrey Shafer.  Welcome to the game.\rquote 
\par He pulled a Smith & Wesson 9mm semiautomatic and fired twice.
\par The woman cried out and grabbed the left side of her chest.  Bright-red blood was already staining her sea-green dress.  Her eyes showed confusion, shock and then rolled back into her forehead.
\par The male agent had a dark hole where his left eye had been.  Shafer knew the man was dead before his head struck the courtyard floor with a loud, satisfying smack.
\par He hadn\rquote t lost anything over the years.  Shafer hurried toward the White Suite and Conqueror.  The gunshots certainly would have been heard.  They wouldn\rquote t expect him to run straight into the trap they\rquote d set.  But here he was.
\par Two maids were pushing a squeaking cleanup cart out of the White Suite.  Had they just turned down Conqueror\rquote s bed?  Left the fat man a box of chocolate mints to nibble?
\par \lquote Get the hell out of here!\rquote   he yelled, and raised his gun.  \lquote Go on now! Run for your lives.\rquote   The Jamaican maids took off as if they had just seen the devil himself.  They would tell their children that they had.
\par Shafer burst in the front door of the suite, and there was Oliver Highsmith freewheeling his chair across the freshly scrubbed floor.
\par \lquote Oliver, it\rquote s you,\rquote  Shafer said.  \lquote I do believe I\rquote ve caught the dreaded Covent Garden killer.  You did those killings, didn\rquote t you?  Fancy that.  Game\rquote s over, Oliver.\rquote 
\par At the same time, Shafer thought, watch him closely.  Be careful with Conqueror.
\par Oliver Highsmith stopped moving, then slowly, rather nimbl
y, turned his wheelchair to face Shafer.  A face-to-face meeting.  This was good.  The best.  Highsmith had controlled Bayer and Whitehead from London, when they were all agents.  The original game, The Four Horsemen, had been his idea, a diversion as he 
eased into retirement.  \lquote Our silly little fantasy game,\rquote  he always called it.
\par He studied Shafer, cold-eyed and measuring.  He was bright; an egghead, but a genius, or so Bayer and Whitehead claimed.
\par \lquote My dear fellow, we\rquote re your friends.  The only ones you have now.  We understand your problem.  Let\rquote s talk things through, Geoffrey.\rquote 
\par Shafer laughed at the fat man\rquote s pathetic lies, his superior and condescending attitude, his nerve.  \lquote That\rquote s not what George Bayer told me.  Why, he said you were going to murder me.  Hell of a way to treat a friend.\rquote 
\par Highsmith didn\rquote t blink, didn\rquote t falter.  \lquote We\rquote re not alone here, Geoff.  They\rquote re at the hotel.  The Security Service team is in the grounds.  They must have followed you.\rquote 
\par \lquote And you, and Bayer, and Whitehead.  I know all that, Oliver.  I met a couple of crackerjack agents outside.  Shot \lquote em dead.  That\rquote s why I have to hurry up, can\rquote t tarry.  The game\rquote s on a clock now.  Lots of ways to lose.
\rquote 
\par \lquote We have to talk, Geoff.\rquote 
\par \lquote Talk, talk, talk.\rquote   Shafer shook his head, frowned, then barked out a laugh.  \lquote No, there\rquote 
s nothing for us to talk about.  Talk is such an overrated bore.  I learned to kill in the field, and I like it much more than talking.  No, I actually love it to death.\rquote 
\par \lquote You are mad,\rquote  Highsmith exclaimed, his grayish-blue eyes widening with fear.  Finally he understood who Shafer was; he wasn\rquote t intellectualizing anymore.  He felt it in his gut.
\par \lquote No actually, I\rquote m not insane.  I know precisely what I\rquote m doing, always have, always will.  I know the difference between good and evil.  Anyway, look who\rquote s talking, the Rider on the White Horse.\rquote 
\par Shafer moved quickly toward Highsmith.  \lquote This isn\rquote t much of a fight - just the way I was taught to perform in Asia.  You\rquote re going to die, Oliver.  Isn\rquote t that a stunning thought?  Still think this is a bloody fantasy game?
\rquote 
\par Suddenly Highsmith jumped to his feet.  Shafer wasn\rquote t surprised.  He knew he couldn\rquote t have committed the murders in London from a wheelchair.  Highsmith was close to six feet and obese, but surprisingly quick for his size. 
 His arms and hands were massive.
\par Shafer was simply faster.  He struck Highsmith with the butt of his gun and Conqueror went crashing down on one knee.  Shafer bludgeoned him a second time, then a third, and Highsmith dropped flat on the floor.  He groaned
 loudly, and slobbered blood and spit.  Shafer kicked the small of his back, kicked a knee, kicked Highsmith\rquote s face.
\par Shafer bent and put the gun barrel against Highsmith\rquote s broad forehead.  He could hear the distant sound of running footsteps slapping down the hall.  Too bad, they were coming for him.  Hurry, hurry.
\par \lquote They\rquote re too late,\rquote  he said to Conqueror.  \lquote No one can save you.  Except me, Conqueror.  What\rquote s the play?  Counsel me.  Should I save the whale?\rquote 
\par \lquote Please, Geoff, no.  You can\rquote t just kill me.  We can still help each other.\rquote 
\par \lquote I\rquote d love to stretch this out, but I really have to dash.  I\rquote m throwing the dice.  In my mind.  Oh, bad news, Oliver.  The game is up.  You just lost.\rquote 
\par He inserted the barrel of his gun into Highsmith\rquote s pulpy right ear and fired.  The gunshot blew Conqueror\rquote s gray matter all over the room, and Shafer\rquote s only regret was that he couldn\rquote 
t have tortured Oliver Highsmith much, much longer than he had.
\par Then Shafer was running away, and he realized something that actually surprised him.  He had something to live for.  This was a wonderful, wonderful game.
\par He wanted to live.
