\par It took two more exhausting days and nights to finish with the local police investigation, but it was good to keep focused and busy.  I no longer had any hope of finding Christine, or discovering what had happened to her.
\par I knew it was remotely possible that Shafer hadn\rquote t taken Christine; that it was some other madman from my past, but I didn\rquote t give that possibility more than a passing thought.  I couldn\rquote 
t go there.  It was too crazy an idea, even for me.
\par I\rquote d been unable to grieve from the start, but now the monstrous finality of Christine\rquote s fate struck me with all of its
 brutal force.  I felt as if my insides had been hollowed out.  The constant, dull ache I had known for so long had become a sharp stab of pain that pierced my heart every waking moment.  I couldn\rquote t stop, yet I felt as if I were never fully awake.

\par Sampson knew what was happening to me.  There was nothing he could say, but he made comforting small talk.
\par Nana called me at the hotel, and I knew it was Sampson\rquote s doing, though both of them denied it.  Jannie and Damon got on the phone, and they were both sweet a
nd kind and full of life and hopefulness.  They even put Rosie the cat on for a friendly long-distance meow.  They didn\rquote t mention Christine, but I knew she was always in their thoughts.
\par On our final night on the island, Sampson and I had dinner with Jones.  We had become friendly, and he finally told me some facts he had withheld for security reasons.  He wanted me to have some closure; he felt I deserved that.
\par Back in 1989, after Shafer arrived in MI6, he was recruited by James Whitehead.  He had reported 
in to Oliver Highsmith, and George Bayer had worked for him.  Shafer had performed at least four sanctions in Asia during the next three years.  It was suspected, but never proved, that he, Whitehead, and Bayer had murdered prostitutes in Manila and Bangk
o
k.  These murders were obviously the precursors to the Jane Does, and the game.  All in all, it had been one of the worst scandals in the history of the Secret Service.  And it had effectively been covered up.  That was how Jones wanted to keep it, and I 
had no worthwhile objection.  There were already more than enough unfortunate stories to keep people cynical about their governments.
\par Our dinner broke up at around eleven and Jones and I promised to keep in touch.  There was one bit of disturbing news, though no one wanted to overstate the significance of it: Geoffrey Shafer\rquote s body still hadn\rquote 
t been found.  Somehow that seemed a fitting end.
\par Sampson and I were due to catch the first flight to Washington on Tuesday morning.  It was scheduled to leave at ten past nine.
\par That morning, the skies were swirling with black clouds.  Heavy rain teemed on our car\rquote s roof all the way from the hotel to the Donald Sangster Airport.  School-kids ran along the side of the road, shielding themselves from the rain with flopping
 banana-tree leaves.
\par The downpour caught us good as we tried to dash out from under the cover of the tin overhang outside the rent-a-car depot.
\par The rain was cool, though, and it felt good on my face and head and on the shirt plastered to my back.
\par \lquote It\rquote ll be real good to be home,\rquote  Sampson said as we finally made it under the cover of a metal roof painted a bright yellow.
\par \lquote I\rquote m ready to go,\rquote  I agreed.  \lquote I miss Damon and Jannie, Nana.  I miss being home.\rquote 
\par \lquote They\rquote ll find the body,\rquote  Sampson said.  \lquote Shafer\rquote s.\rquote 
\par \lquote I knew who you meant.\rquote 
\par The rain hammered the airport\rquote s roof without mercy, and I was thinking how much I hated to fly on days like this, but it would be good to be home, to be able to end this nightmare.  It had invaded my soul, taken over my life.  In a way, 
I suppose it was as much a game as any that
\par Shafer had played.  The murder case had obsessed me for over a year, and that was enough.
\par Christine had asked me to give it up, Nana had asked, too, and I hadn\rquote t listened.  Maybe I hadn\rquote t been able to see my life
 and actions as clearly as I did now.  I was the Dragonslayer, and all that it meant, the good and the bad.  In the end, I held myself responsible for Christine\rquote s kidnapping and murder.
\par Sampson and I tramped past the colorful concession stands without any real interest, barely a passing nod.  Street hawkers, called higglers, were selling wooden jewelry and other carvings, but also Jamaican coffee and cocoa.
\par Each of us carried a black duffel bag.  We didn\rquote t exactly look like vacationers, I was thinking.  We still looked like policemen.
\par I heard a voice calling loudly from behind, and I turned back to look at the commotion coming up from the rear.
\par It was the Jamaican detective, John Anthony, calling out my name in the noisy terminal, coming our way in a big hurry.  He was walking rapidly, a few steps ahead of Andrew Jones, who looked powerfully dismayed.
\par Jones and Anthony at the airport?  What in God\rquote s name was happening now?  What could possibly have gone wrong?
\par \lquote The Weasel?\rquote   I said, and it came out like a curse.
\par Sampson and I stopped, and they finally caught up with us.  I almost didn\rquote t want to hear what they had to tell us.
\par \lquote You have to go back with us, Alex.  Come with me.\rquote   Jones said, slightly out of breath.  \lquote It\rquote s about Christine Johnson.  Something\rquote s turned up.  Come.\rquote 
\par \lquote What is it?  What\rquote s happened?\rquote   I asked Jones, then Detective Anthony, when the Englishman was slow in answering.
\par Anthony hesitated, but then he said, \lquote We don\rquote t know for sure.  It could be nothing at all.  Someone claims to have seen her, though.  She may be here in Jamaica, after all.  Come with us.\rquote 
\par I couldn\rquote t believe what he had just told me.  I felt Sampson\rquote s arm wrap tightly around me, but everything else seemed unreal, as in a dream.
\par It wasn\rquote t over yet.
