\par \lquote No!\rquote 
\par Detective Anthony got out of the car with both hands held high.  So did Sampson, Jones and I.
\par There was the beat of traditional drums coming from the woods directly behind the main house.  A pair of lounging dogs raised their lazy heads to look at us, and barked a few times.  My heart was thundering faster now.
\par I didn\rquote t like the way this was going.
\par Another one of the men called to us, \lquote I and I would like you to leave.\rquote 
\par I recognized the phrase of speech.  The double pronoun represented the speaker and God, who live together in each person.
\par \lquote Patrick Moss is in jail.  I\rquote m Detective Anthony from Kingston.  This is Detective Sampson and Detective Cross.  You have a woman here.  You call her Beatitude.\rquote 
\par Beatitude?  Could it be Christine?
\par One of the men with a machete hanging from one hand glared and spoke to Anthony.  \lquote Galang \lquote bout yuh business.  Lef me nuh.  Nah woman here.  Nah woman.\rquote 
\par \lquote This is my business and we won\rquote t leave you alone.\rquote   I said, surprising the man that I understood his dialect.  But I know Rastaman from DC.
\par \lquote Nah woman here.  Nah American.\rquote   the man repeated angrily, looking directly at me.
\par Andrew Jones spoke up.  \lquote We want the American woman, then we\rquote ll leave.  Your friend Patrick Moss will be home by tonight.  You can deal with him in your own way.\rquote 
\par \lquote Nah American woman here.\rquote   The original speaker spat defiantly on the ground.  \lquote Turn around, go back.\rquote 
\par \lquote You know James Whitehead?  You know Shafer?\rquote   Jones said.
\par They didn\rquote t deny it.  I doubted we\rquote d get anymore from them than that.
\par \lquote I love her,\rquote  I told them.  \lquote I can\rquote t leave.  Her name is Christine.\rquote 
\par My mouth was still dry and I couldn\rquote t breathe very well.  \lquote She was kidnapped a year ago.  We know she was brought here.\rquote 
\par Sampson took out his Glock and held it loosely at his side.  He stared at the four men, who continued to glare back at us.  I touched the handle of my gun, still in its holster.  I didn\rquote t want a gunfight.
\par \lquote We can cause you a whole lot of trouble,\rquote  Sampson said, in a low, rumbling voice.  \lquote You won\rquote t believe how much trouble is coming your way.\rquote 
\par Finally, I just walked forward on a worn path through the tall grass.  I passed by the men, lightly brushing against one of them.
\par No one tried to stop me.  I could smell ganja and sweat on their work clothes.  Tension was building up inside me.
\par Sampson followed me, no more than a step or two behind.  \lquote I\rquote m watching them,\rquote  he said.  \lquote Nobody\rquote s doing anything yet.\rquote 
\par \lquote Doesn\rquote t matter.\rquote   I said.  \lquote I have to see if she\rquote s here.\rquote 
