\par An older woman with long and wildly frazzled gray-and-white hair stepped out of the front door as I reached the scarred, unpainted steps.  Her eyes were ringed with redness.
\par \lquote Come with me,\rquote  she sighed.  \lquote Come along.  You nah need no weapon.\rquote 
\par For the first time in many months I allowed myself to feel the tiniest flash of hope.  I didn\rquote t have any reason to, just the rumor that a woman had been kept here against her will.
\par Beatitude?  Something to do with blessedness and happiness?  Could it be Christine?
\par The old woman walked unsteadily around the house and through light bushes, trees, and ferns out back.  About sixty or seventy yards into thickening woods she came to half-a-dozen small shacks, and s
he stopped.  The shacks were made of wood, bamboo, and corrugated metal.
\par She walked forward again and stopped at the next-to-last shack in the group.
\par She took out a key attached to a leather strap around her waist.  She then inserted the key and jiggled it.
\par She pushed the door forward and it creaked loudly on a rusty hinge.
\par I looked inside and saw a plain, neat, and clean room.  Someone had written The Lord Is My Shepherd in black paint on the wall.
\par No one was there.
\par No Beatitude.
\par No Christine.
\par I let my eyes fall shut.  Desperation enveloped me.
\par My eyes slowly opened.  I didn\rquote t understand why I had been led to this empty room, this old shack in the woods.  My heart was ripped in two again.  Was it some kind of trap?
\par The Weasel?  Shafer?  Was he here?
\par Someone stepped out from behind a small folding screen in one corner of the room.  I felt as if I were in free fall, and a small gasp came out of my mouth.
\par I didn\rquote t know what I had been expecting, but not this.  Sampson put out his hand to steady me.  I was barely aware of his touch.
\par Christine gently stepped into the shafts of sunlight coming from the single window in the shack.  I had never expected to see her again.
\par She was much thinner and her hair was braided and longer than I\rquote d ever seen it.  But she had the same wise, beautiful brown eyes.  Neither of us was able to speak at first.  It was the strangest moment of my life.
\par I had gone cold all over and everything was moving in slow motion.  It seemed supematurally quiet in the small room.
\par Christine was holding a light-yellow blanket, and I could see a baby\rquote 
s head just peeking above the crown of the covers.  I walked forward even though my legs were trembling and threatening to buckle.  I could hear the baby softly cooing in the nest of blankets.
\par \lquote Oh, Christine, Christine,\rquote  I finally managed.
\par Tears welled in her eyes, and then in mine.  We both stepped forward, and then I was awkwardly holding her.  The little baby peacefully gazed up into both our faces.
\par \lquote This is our baby, and he probably saved my life.  He takes after you,\rquote 
 Christine said.  Then we kissed gently, and it was so sweet and tender.  We held on for dear, dear life.  We melted into each other.  Neither of us could believe this was actually happening.
\par \lquote I call him Alex.  You were always right here,\rquote  Christine told me.  \lquote You were always with me.\rquote 
