\par His name was Frederick Neuman, and he liked to think of himself as a citizen of the European Community rather than any single country, but if any
one asked he claimed to be German.  His head was shaved close and it made him look severe, but also more impressive, he thought, which was an amazing accomplishment.
\par He would be remembered as \lquote quite tall, thin and bald\rquote , or as \lquote an interesting artist type\rquote , and several people did see him that week in the Chelsea area of London.  He wanted to be remembered.  That was important.
\par He shopped, or at least window-shopped, on the King\rquote s Road and Sloane Street.
\par He went to the cinema on Kensington High Street.
\par And Waterstone\rquote s bookshop.
\par Nights, he would have a pint or two at the King\rquote s Head.  He mostly kept to himself at the pub.
\par He had a master plan.  Another game was beginning.
\par He saw Lucy and the twins at Safeway one afternoon.  He watched them from a safe distance across rows of baked beans and aisles of shoppers.  No harm, no foul, no problem for anybody.
\par He couldn\rquote t resist the challenge though.  The dice started to play in his head.  They rattled the number he wanted to hear.
\par He kept walking closer and closer to the family, careful to keep his face slightly averted, just in case, but still watching Lucy out of the corner of his eye, watching the twins, who were perhaps more dangerous.
\par Lucy was examining some wild Scottish salmon.  She finally noticed him, he was sure, but she didn\rquote t recognize who he was - obviously.  Neither did the twins.  Dumb, silly little girls - mirrors of their mother.
\par The game was on again - so delicious.  He\rquote d been away from it for a while.  He had book money, his advance, which he kept in Switzerland.  He had bummed around the Caribbean after his escape by boat from Jamaica.  He\rquote 
d gone to San Juan and been tempted to act up there.  He\rquote d finally traveled to Europe, to Rome, Milan, Paris, Frankfurt, Dublin - and at last home to London.  He\rquote d 
only strayed a couple of times on the whole trip.  He was such a careful boy now.
\par It felt just like old times as he got oh so close to Lucy in the shopping aisle.  Jesus, his physical tics were back.  He was tapping his foot nervously and shaking out his hands.
\par He\rquote d have thought she might have noticed that, but she was such a vacuous blonde cow, such a cipher, a waste of time; even now, as he got closer and closer, only a foot or two away.
\par \lquote Oh Loo-cy...  it\rquote s Ricky,\rquote  he said, and grinned and grinned.  \lquote It\rquote s me, darling.\rquote 
\par Swish.  Swish.  He swiped at her twice, back and forth, as they passed like strangers in the aisle at Safeway.  The blows barely crisscrossed Lucy\rquote s throat, but they cut her inches deep.
\par She dropped to her bony knees, both hands clutching her neck as if she were strangling herself.  And then she saw who it was, and her blue eyes filled with complete shock and pain and what seemed to be terrible disappointment.
\par \lquote Geoffrey,\rquote  she managed in a gurgling voice, as blood bubbled from her open mouth.
\par Her last word on earth.  His name.
\par Beautiful for Shafer to hear, recognition that he craved, revenge against all of them.  He turned away, forced himself to, before he did the twins as well.
\par He was never seen again in Chelsea, but everyone would remember him for as long as they lived.
\par God, would they remember.
\par That tall, bald monster.
\par The one in all-black clothes, the inhuman freak.
\par The heartless killer who had committed so many awful murders that even he had lost count.
